# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sotaro-kita
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] David McNeill is a professor of the University of Chicago in Illinois, and a writer.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill studied for and was awarded a Bachelor of Arts in 1953 and a Doctor of Philosophy in 1962, both in psychology, at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] He went on to study at the Center for Cognitive Studies, Harvard University in 1963.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] In 1995, McNeill won the Award for Outstanding Faculty Achievement, University of Chicago; and in 1995 he was awarded the Gordon J.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Laing Award from the University of Chicago Press for the book *Hand and Mind*.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill specializes in psycholinguistics, and in particular scientific research into the relationship of language to thought, and the gestures that accompany discourse.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] This and other research has formed the subject matter of a number of books which McNeill has written through his career.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The "growth point" is a key theoretical concept in McNeill's approach to psycholinguistics and is central to his work on gestures, specifically those spontaneous and unwitting hand movements that regularly accompany informal speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The growth point, or GP, posits that gestures and speech are unified and need to be considered jointly.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] For McNeill, gestures are in effect (or, McNeill would say, in reality) the speaker's thought in action, and integral components of speech, not merely accompaniments or additions.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Much evidence supports this idea, but its full implications have not always been recognized.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill argues that thought is multimodal: both vocal-linguistic and manual-gestural, and the resulting semiotic opposition fuels change.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] In terms of semiotics, as a kind of sign, a gesture is "global" (in that the meanings of the "parts"—the hand shapes, space, direction, articulation–-depend in a top-down fashion on the meaning of the whole) and "synthetic" (in that several meanings are bundled into one gesture).
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Speech contrasts on each of these points: it is bottom-up, analytic and combinatoric.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Speech and gesture, taken together, comprise minimal units of human linguistic cognition.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The linguistic component of speech categorizes the visual and actional imagery of the gesture; the imagery of the gesture grounds the linguistic categories in a visual spatial frame.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill employs the concept of "material carriers", a phrase used by Vygotsky to refer to the embodiment of meaning in enactments or material experiences to further develop the concepts of Mead's Loop and the GP.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] A material carrier enhances the symbolization's representational power.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The concept implies that the gesture, "the actual motion of the gesture itself", is a dimension of meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] This enhancement is possible if the gesture "is" the very image; not an "expression" or "representation" of it, but "it".
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] From this viewpoint, a gesture is an image in its most developed: that is, its most materially, naturally embodied form.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The absence of a gesture is the converse, an image in its least material form.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The material carrier concept thus helps explain how an imagery-language dialectic can take place in absence of gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] When no gesture occurs, there is still global-synthetic imagery in a dialectic with linguistic categorization, but we experience it at the "lowest level of materialization".
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] It is not an alteration of the dialectic of its essentials-–the simultaneous rendering of meaning in opposite semiotic modes-–but a bleached version of it.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill furthers this conception of the material carrier by turning to Maurice Merleau-Ponty for insight into the duality of gesture and language.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Gesture, the instantaneous, global, nonconventional component, is "not an external accompaniment" of speech, which is the sequential, analytic, combinatoric component; it is not a "representation" of meaning, but instead meaning "inhabits" it.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] For McNeill, the GP is a mechanism geared to this "existential significance" of speech, this "taking up a position in the world".
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Gesture, as part of the GP, is inhabited by the same "living meaning" that inhabits the word (and beyond, the whole of a discourse).
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] A deeper answer to the query, therefore-–when we see a gesture, what are we seeing?--is that we see part of the speaker's current cognitive being, "her very mental existence", at the moment it occurs.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] This too is part of the origin of language by Mead's Loop (and explains the gestural leakage of lies.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] By performing the gesture, a core idea is brought into concrete existence and becomes part of the speaker's own existence at that moment.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] A gesture is not a representation, or is not only such: it is a form of being.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] From a first-person perspective, the gesture is part of the immediate existence of the speaker.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Gestures (and words, etc., as well) are themselves thinking in one of its many forms, not only expressions of thought, "but thought, i.e., cognitive being, itself".
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] To the speaker, gesture and speech are not only "messages" or communications, but are a way of cognitively existing, of cognitively being, at the moment of speaking.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] To make a gesture, from this perspective, is to bring thought into existence on a concrete plane, just as writing out a word can have a similar effect.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The greater the felt departure of the thought from the immediate context, the more likely is its materialization in a gesture, because of this contribution to being.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Conversely, when "newsworthiness" is minimal materialization diminishes and in some cases disappears, even though a GP is active; in these cases gestures may cease while (empty) speech continues, or vice versa, speech ceases and a vague gesture takes place.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Thus, gestures are more or less elaborated and GPs more or less materialized depending on the importance of material realization to the "existence" of the thought.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] In terms of the origin of language, the GP "predicts" (of the remote past) that whatever evolved led to a GP system of semiotic oppositions.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] This provides an empirical test of all theories on the origin of language: Can the theory in question explain the observed speech-gesture-thought unity of human cognition?
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The widely popular "gesture-first" theory, according to which language began as pure gesture without speech, fails this test.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] In fact, it fails it twice, predicting what did not evolve (that speech supplanted gesture) and not predicting what did evolve (our own speech-gesture unity).
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] An alternative, which McNeill calls "Mead's Loop" after the philosopher George Herbert Mead, explains this unity.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] It too claims that gesture was essential to the origin of language, but not because it was "primitive" or more accessible.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Rather, it says that speech could not have evolved without gesture; neither could gesture have evolved without speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Speech and gesture originated together, at the same time, in response to the same selection pressures.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Mead's Loop and the mirror neuron "twist" would be naturally selected in scenarios where sensing one's own actions as social is advantageous.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] For example, in imparting information to infants, where it gives the adult the sense of being an instructor as opposed to being just a doer with an onlooker, as is the case with chimpanzees.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Entire cultural practices of childrearing depend upon this sense.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Self-awareness as an agent is necessary for this advantage to take hold.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] For Mead's Loop to have been selected the adult must be sensitive to her own gestures as social actions.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The link between the GP and self-aware agency also appears in children's language development, which can be linked to the origin of language in a version of the long-dismissed "ontogeny recapitulates phylogeny" hypothesis of recapitulation theory.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill considers that when something emerges in current-day ontogenesis only at a certain stage of development, the original natural selection of the feature (if there was any) might have taken place in a similar psychological milieu in phylogenesis.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] This opens a window onto the mindset of the creature in which the Mead's Loop "twist" was evolving.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] As a mode of reasoning, it exploits the fact that children's intellectual status is not fixed but changing.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Thus, McNeill argues, we look for new states that seem pegged to steps in the ontogenesis of GPs and Mead's Loop underlying them, and consider these steps as possible signals from ancient phylogenesis.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] Evidence shows that self-aware agency could be such a signal.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] The theory of mind (which is really awareness of other perspectives) also emerges about this time, and likewise depends on self-aware agency.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] McNeill's books have received coverage in a number of academic journals and in the general press.
[src:sotaro-kita/david-mcneill] A 1991 article in the *Chicago Reader*; a 2006 article in the *Scientific American, Mind* magazine; and a 2008 article in *Boston Globe* describe McNeill's work on the language of gesture in detail.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A **Doctor of Philosophy** (**PhD**, **DPhil**; Latin: *philosophiae doctor* or *doctor in philosophia*) is a terminal degree that usually denotes the highest level of academic achievement in a given discipline and is awarded following a course of graduate study and original research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The name of the degree is most often abbreviated PhD (or, at times, as Ph.D. in North America) and is pronounced as three separate letters (/ˌpiːeɪtʃˈdiː/ *PEE-aych-DEE*).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The University of Oxford uses the alternative abbreviation "DPhil".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] PhDs are awarded for programs across the whole breadth of academic fields.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Since it is an earned research degree, those studying for a PhD are required to produce original research that expands the boundaries of knowledge, normally in the form of a dissertation, and, in some cases, defend their work before a panel of other experts in the field.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In many fields, the completion of a PhD is typically required for employment as a university professor, researcher, or scientist.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In the context of the Doctor of Philosophy and other similarly titled degrees, the term "philosophy" does not refer to the field or academic discipline of philosophy, but is used in a broader sense in accordance with its original Greek meaning, which is "love of wisdom".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A PhD candidate must submit a project, thesis, or dissertation often consisting of a body of original academic research, which is in principle worthy of publication in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In many countries, a candidate must defend this work before a panel of expert examiners appointed by the university.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Universities sometimes award other types of doctorate besides the PhD, such as the Doctor of Musical Arts (DMA) for music performers, Doctor of Juridical Science (SJD) for legal scholars and the Doctor of Education (EdD) for studies in education.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In 2005 the European University Association defined the "Salzburg Principles", 10 basic principles for third-cycle degrees (doctorates) within the Bologna Process.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The specific requirements to earn a PhD degree vary considerably according to the country, institution, and time period, from entry-level research degrees to higher doctorates.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] During the studies that lead to the degree, the student is called a *doctoral student* or *PhD student*; a student who has completed any necessary coursework and related examinations and is working on their thesis/dissertation is sometimes known as a *doctoral candidate* or *PhD candidate*.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A student attaining this level may be granted a Candidate of Philosophy degree at some institutions or may be granted a master's degree *en route* to the doctoral degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Sometimes this status is also colloquially known as "ABD", meaning "all but dissertation".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] PhD graduates may undertake a postdoc in the process of transitioning from study to academic tenure.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Individuals who have earned the Doctor of Philosophy degree use the title *Doctor* (often abbreviated "Dr" or "Dr."), although the etiquette associated with this usage may be subject to the professional ethics of the particular scholarly field, culture, or society.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Those who teach at universities or work in academic, educational, or research fields are usually addressed by this title "professionally and socially in a salutation or conversation".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Alternatively, holders may use post-nominal letters such as "Ph.D.", "PhD", or "DPhil", depending on the awarding institution.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] It is, however, traditionally considered incorrect to use both the title and post-nominals together, although usage in that regard has been evolving over time.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The first doctoral degree was awarded at the University of Paris around 1150.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In the universities of Medieval Europe, study was organized in four faculties: the basic faculty of arts, and the three higher faculties of theology, medicine, and laws (canon law and civil law).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The doctorates in the higher faculties were quite different from the current PhD degree in that they were awarded for advanced scholarship, not original research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] No dissertation or original work was required, only lengthy residency requirements and examinations.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] All of these faculties awarded intermediate degrees (bachelors of arts, theology, laws and medicine) and final degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Besides these degrees, there was the licentiate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Originally this was a license to teach, awarded shortly before the award of the master's or doctoral degree by the diocese in which the university was located, but later it evolved into an academic degree in its own right, in particular in the continental universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The full course of studies might, for example, lead in succession to the degrees of Bachelor of Arts, Licentiate of Arts, Master of Arts, or Bachelor of Medicine, Licentiate of Medicine, or Doctor of Medicine, but before the early modern era, many exceptions to this existed.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Most students left the university without becoming masters of arts, whereas regulars (members of monastic orders) could skip the arts faculty entirely.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] This situation changed in the early 19th century through the educational reforms in Germany, most strongly embodied in the model of the University of Berlin, founded in 1810 and controlled by the Prussian government.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Whereas in the Middle Ages the arts faculty had a set curriculum, based upon the trivium and the quadrivium, by the 19th century it had come to house all the courses of study in subjects now commonly referred to as sciences and humanities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Professors across the humanities and sciences focused on their advanced research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] These reforms proved extremely successful, and fairly quickly the German universities started attracting foreign students, notably from the United States.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The American students would go to Germany to obtain a PhD after having studied for a bachelor's degree at an American college.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In Germany, the name of the doctorate was adapted after the philosophy faculty started being split up − e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Dr. rer. nat. for doctorates in the faculty of natural sciences − but in most of the English-speaking world the name "Doctor of Philosophy" was retained for research doctorates in all disciplines.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The PhD degree and similar awards spread across Europe in the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Research degrees first appeared in the UK in the late 19th century in the shape of the Doctor of Science (DSc or ScD) and other such "higher doctorates".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The University of London introduced the DSc in 1860, but as an advanced study course, following on directly from the BSc, rather than a research degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The first higher doctorate in the modern sense was Durham University's DSc, introduced in 1882.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] This was soon followed by other universities, including the University of Cambridge establishing its ScD in the same year and the University of London transforming its DSc into a research degree in 1885.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] These were, however, very advanced degrees, rather than research-training degrees at the PhD level.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In 1917, the current PhD degree was introduced, along the lines of the American and German model, and quickly became popular with both British and foreign students.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In English (but not Scottish) universities, the Faculty of Arts had become dominant by the early 19th century.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Indeed, the higher faculties had largely atrophied, since medical training had shifted to teaching hospitals, the legal training for the common law system was provided by the Inns of Court (with some minor exceptions, see Doctors' Commons), and few students undertook formal study in theology.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The reforms at the Humboldt University transformed the Faculty of Philosophy or Arts (and its more recent successors such as the Faculty of Sciences) from a lower faculty into one on a par with the Faculties of Law and Medicine.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Until the mid-19th century, advanced degrees were not a criterion for professorships at most colleges.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] That began to change as the more ambitious scholars at major schools went to Germany for one to three years to obtain a PhD in the sciences or humanities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Graduate schools slowly emerged in the United States.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In 1852, the first honorary PhD in the nation was given at Bucknell University in Lewisburg, Pennsylvania to Ebenezer Newton Elliott.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Nine years later, in 1861, Yale University awarded three PhDs: to Eugene Schuyler in philosophy and psychology, Arthur Williams Wright in physics, and James Morris Whiton Jr. in classics.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Over the following two decades, Harvard University, New York University, Princeton University, and the University of Pennsylvania, also began granting the degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Major shifts toward graduate education were foretold by the opening of Clark University in 1887, which offered only graduate programs, and the Johns Hopkins University, which focused on its PhD program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] By the 1890s, Harvard, Columbia, Michigan and Wisconsin were building major graduate programs, whose alumni were hired by new research universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] By 1900, 300 PhDs were awarded annually, most of them by six universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] It was no longer necessary to study in Germany.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] However, half of the institutions awarding earned PhDs in 1899 were undergraduate institutions that granted the degree for work done away from campus.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Degrees awarded by universities without legitimate PhD programs accounted for about a third of the 382 doctorates recorded by the US Department of Education in 1900, of which another 8–10% were honorary.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The awarding of PhD as an honorary degree was banned by the Board of Regents of the University of the State of New York in 1897.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] This had a nation-wide impact, and after 1907, less than 10 honorary PhDs were awarded in the United States each year.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The last authenticated PhD awarded *honoris causa* was awarded in 1937 to Bing Crosby by Gonzaga University.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] At the start of the 20th century, U.S. universities were held in low regard internationally and many American students were still traveling to Europe for PhDs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The lack of centralised authority meant anyone could start a university and award PhDs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In Germany, the national government funded the universities and the research programs of the leading professors.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] It was impossible for professors who were not approved by Berlin to train graduate students.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In the United States, by contrast, private universities and state universities alike were independent of the federal government.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Independence was high, but funding was low.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The breakthrough came from private foundations, which began regularly supporting research in science and history; large corporations sometimes supported engineering programs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The postdoctoral fellowship was established by the Rockefeller Foundation in 1919.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Meanwhile, the leading universities, in cooperation with the learned societies, set up a network of scholarly journals.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] "Publish or perish" became the formula for faculty advancement in the research universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] After World War II, state universities across the country expanded greatly in undergraduate enrollment, and eagerly added research programs leading to masters or doctoral degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Their graduate faculties had to have a suitable record of publication and research grants.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Late in the 20th century, "publish or perish" became increasingly important in colleges and smaller universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Detailed requirements for the award of a PhD degree vary throughout the world and even from school to school.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] It is sometimes required for the student to hold an Honours degree or a Master's degree with high academic standing, in order to be considered for a PhD program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In Canada, India, Sweden and Denmark, for example, many universities require coursework in addition to research for PhD degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In other countries (such as the UK) there is generally no such condition, though this varies by university and field.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Some individual universities or departments specify additional requirements for students not already in possession of a bachelor's degree or equivalent or higher.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In order to submit a successful PhD admission application, copies of academic transcripts, letters of recommendation, a research proposal, and a personal statement are often required.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Most universities also invite for a special interview before admission.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A candidate must submit a project, thesis, or dissertation often consisting of a body of original academic research, which is in principle worthy of publication in a peer-reviewed context.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Moreover, some PhD programs, especially in science, require one to three published articles in peer-reviewed journals.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Some universities in the non-English-speaking world have begun adopting similar standards to those of the anglophone PhD degree for their research doctorates (see the Bologna process).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A PhD student or candidate is conventionally required to study on campus under close supervision.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] With the popularity of distance education and e-learning technologies, some universities now accept students enrolled into a distance education part-time mode.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In a "sandwich PhD" program, PhD candidates do not spend their entire study period at the same university.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Instead, the PhD candidates spend the first and last periods of the program at their home universities and in between conduct research at another institution or field research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Occasionally a "sandwich PhD" will be awarded by two universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] It is possible to broaden the field of study pursued by a PhD student by the addition of a minor subject of study within a different discipline.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A career in academia generally requires a PhD, although in some countries it is possible to reach relatively high positions without a doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] In North America, professors are increasingly being required to have a PhD, and the percentage of faculty with a PhD may be used as a university ratings measure.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The motivation may also include increased salary, but in many cases, this is not the result.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Casey of the University of Warwick, U.K, suggests that, over all subjects, PhDs provide an earnings premium of 26% over non-accredited graduates, but notes that master's degrees already provide a premium of 23% and a bachelor's 14%.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] While this is a small return to the individual (or even an overall deficit when tuition and lost earnings during training are accounted for), he claims there are significant benefits to society for the extra research training.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] However, some research suggests that overqualified workers are often less satisfied and less productive at their jobs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] These difficulties are increasingly being felt by graduates of professional degrees, such as law school, looking to find employment.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] PhD students may need to take on debt to undertake their degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] A PhD is sometimes felt to be a necessary qualification in certain areas of employment, such as in foreign policy think-tanks: *U.S.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] News & World Report* wrote in 2013 that "[i]f having a master's degree at the minimum is *de rigueur* in Washington's foreign policy world, it is no wonder many are starting to feel that the PhD is a necessary escalation, another case of costly signaling to potential employers".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Similarly, an article on the Australian public service states that "credentialism in the public service is seeing a dramatic increase in the number of graduate positions going to PhDs and masters degrees becoming the base entry level qualification".
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The U.S. higher education system often offers little incentive to move students through PhD programs quickly and may even provide incentives to slow them down.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] To counter this problem, the United States introduced the Doctor of Arts degree in 1970 with seed money from the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] The aim of the Doctor of Arts degree was to shorten the time needed to complete the degree by focusing on pedagogy over research, although the Doctor of Arts still contains a significant research component.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Germany is one of the few nations engaging these issues, and it has been doing so by reconceptualising PhD programs to be training for careers, outside academia, but still at high-level positions.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] This development can be seen in the extensive number of PhD holders, typically from the fields of law, engineering, and economics, at the very top corporate and administrative positions.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Taylor opined in 2011 in *Nature* that total reform of PhD programs in almost every field is necessary in the U.S. and that pressure to make the necessary changes will need to come from many sources (students, administrators, public and private sectors, etc.).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Other articles in *Nature* have also examined the issue of PhD reform.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p01] Freeman Dyson, then professor emeritus at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, was opposed to the PhD system and did not have a PhD degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The UNESCO, in its International Standard Classification of Education (ISCED), states that: "Programmes to be classified at ISCED level 8 are referred to in many ways around the world such as PhD, DPhil, D.Lit, D.Sc, LL.D, Doctorate or similar terms.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] However, programmes with a similar name to 'doctor' should only be included in ISCED level 8 if they satisfy the criteria described in Paragraph 263.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In Argentina, the admission to a PhD program at public Argentine University requires the full completion of a Master's degree or a Licentiate degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Non-Argentine Master's titles are generally accepted into a PhD program when the degree comes from a recognized university.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Others apply for funds to CONICET, the national public body of scientific and technical research, which typically awards more than a thousand scholarships each year for this purpose, thus guaranteeing many PhD candidates remain within the system.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Upon completion of at least two years' research and coursework as a graduate student, a candidate must demonstrate truthful and original contributions to their specific field of knowledge within a frame of academic excellence.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The doctoral candidate's work should be presented in a dissertation or thesis prepared under the supervision of a tutor or director and reviewed by a Doctoral Committee.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] This committee should be composed of examiners that are external to the program, and at least one of them should also be external to the institution.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The academic degree of Doctor, respective to the correspondent field of science that the candidate has contributed with original and rigorous research, is received after a successful defense of the candidate's dissertation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Admission to a PhD program in Australia requires applicants to demonstrate capacity to undertake research in the proposed field of study.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The standard requirement is a bachelor honours degree with either first-class or upper second-class honours.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Research master's degrees and coursework master's degrees with a 25% research component are usually considered equivalent.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] It is also possible for research master's degree students to "upgrade" to PhD candidature after demonstrating sufficient progress.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] PhD students are sometimes offered a scholarship to study for their PhD degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The most common of these was the government-funded Australian Postgraduate Award (APA) until its dissolution in 2017.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] It was replaced by Research Training Program (RTP), awarded to students of "exceptional research potential", which provides a living stipend to students of approximately A$34,000 a year (tax-free).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] RTPs are paid for a duration of 3 years, while a 6-month extension is usually possible upon citing delays out of the control of the student.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Some universities also fund a similar scholarship that matches the APA amount.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Due to a continual increase in living costs, many PhD students are forced to live under the poverty line.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In addition to the more common RTP and university scholarships, Australian students have other sources of scholarship funding, coming from industry, private enterprise, and organisations.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] All fees are paid for by the Australian government, except for the SSAF, under the Research Training Program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] International students and coursework master's degree students must pay course fees unless they receive a scholarship to cover them.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Most Australian PhD programs do not have a required coursework component.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The credit points attached to the degree are all in the product of the research, which is usually an 80,000-word thesis that makes a significant new contribution to the field.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The PhD thesis is sent to external examiners who are experts in the field of research and who have not been involved in the work.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Examiners are nominated by the candidate's university, and their identities are often not revealed to the candidate until the examination is complete.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A formal oral defence is generally not part of the examination of the thesis, largely because of the distances that would need to be travelled by the overseas examiners; however, since 2016, there is a trend toward implementing this in many Australian universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At the University of South Australia, PhD candidates who started after January 2016 now undertake an oral defence via an online conference with two examiners.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Admission to a doctoral programme at a university in Canada typically requires completion of a Master's degree in a related field, with sufficiently high grades and proven research ability.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In some cases, a student may progress directly from an Honours Bachelor's degree to a PhD program; other programs allow a student to fast-track to a doctoral program after one year of outstanding work in a Master's program (without having to complete the Master's).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] An application package typically includes a research proposal, letters of reference, transcripts, and in some cases, a writing sample or Graduate Record Examinations scores.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A common criterion for prospective PhD students is the comprehensive or qualifying examination, a process that often commences in the second year of a graduate program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Generally, successful completion of the qualifying exam permits continuance in the graduate program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Formats for this examination include oral examination by the student's faculty committee (or a separate qualifying committee), or written tests designed to demonstrate the student's knowledge in a specialized area (see below) or both.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At English-speaking universities, a student may also be required to demonstrate English language abilities, usually by achieving an acceptable score on a standard examination (for example the Test of English as a Foreign Language).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Depending on the field, the student may also be required to demonstrate ability in one or more additional languages.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A prospective student applying to French-speaking universities may also have to demonstrate some English language ability.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] While some students work outside the university (or at student jobs within the university), in some programs students are advised (or must agree) not to devote more than ten hours per week to activities (e.g., employment) outside of their studies, particularly if they have been given funding.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] For large and prestigious scholarships, such as those from NSERC and Fonds québécois de la recherche sur la nature et les technologies, this is an absolute requirement.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At some Canadian universities, most PhD students receive an award equivalent to part or all of the tuition amount for the first four years (this is sometimes called a tuition deferral or tuition waiver).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Other sources of funding include teaching assistantships and research assistantships; experience as a teaching assistant is encouraged but not requisite in many programs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Some programs may require all PhD candidates to teach, which may be done under the supervision of their supervisor or regular faculty.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Besides these sources of funding, there are also various competitive scholarships, bursaries, and awards available, such as those offered by the federal government via NSERC, CIHR, or SSHRC.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In general, the first two years of study are devoted to completion of coursework and the comprehensive examinations.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At this stage, the student is known as a "PhD student" or "doctoral student." It is usually expected that the student will have completed most of their required coursework by the end of this stage.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Furthermore, it is usually required that by the end of eighteen to thirty-six months after the first registration, the student will have successfully completed the comprehensive exams.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Upon successful completion of the comprehensive exams, the student becomes known as a "PhD candidate." From this stage on, the bulk of the student's time will be devoted to their own research, culminating in the completion of a PhD thesis or dissertation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The final requirement is an oral defense of the thesis, which is open to the public in some, but not all, universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At most Canadian universities, the time needed to complete a PhD degree typically ranges from four to six years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Alternative arrangements exist whereby a student is allowed to let their registration in the program lapse at the end of six years and re-register once the thesis is completed in draft form.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The general rule is that graduate students are obligated to pay tuition until the initial thesis submission has been received by the thesis office.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In other words, if a PhD student defers or delays the initial submission of their thesis they remain obligated to pay fees until such time that the thesis has been received in good standing.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In China, doctoral programs can be applied directly after obtaining a bachelor's degree or applied after obtaining a master's degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Those who directly apply for a doctoral program after a bachelor's degree usually need four to five years to obtain a doctorate and will not be awarded a master's degree during the period.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The courses at the doctoral level are mainly completed in the first and second years, and the remaining years are spent doing experiments/research and writing papers.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] At most universities, the maximum duration of doctoral study is 7 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] If a doctoral student does not complete their degree within 7 years, it is likely that they can only obtain a study certificate without any degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] China has thirteen statutory types of academic degrees, which also apply to doctorates.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Despite the naming difference, all these thirteen types of doctoral degrees are research and academic degrees that are equivalent to PhD degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In international academic communication, Chinese doctoral degree recipients sometimes translate their doctoral degree names to *PhD in Discipline* (such as *PhD in Engineering, Computer Science*) to facilitate peer understanding.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In Colombia, the PhD course admission may require a master's degree (Magíster) in some universities, specially public universities.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] However, it could also be applied for a direct doctorate in specific cases, according to the jury's recommendations on the thesis proposal.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Most of postgraduate students in Colombia must finance their tuition fees by means of teaching assistant seats or research works.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Some institutions such as Colciencias, Colfuturo, CeiBA, and Icetex grant scholarships or provide awards in the form of forgivable loans.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] After two or two and a half years, it is expected that the research work of the doctoral candidate be submitted in the form of oral qualification, where suggestions and corrections about the research hypothesis and methodology, as well as on the course of the research work, are performed.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The PhD degree is only received after a successful defense of the candidate's thesis is performed (four or five years after the enrollment), most of the time also requiring the most important results having been published in at least one peer-reviewed high-impact international journal.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In Finland, the degree of *filosofian tohtori* (abbreviated *FT*) is awarded by traditional universities, such as University of Helsinki.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A Master's degree is required, and the doctorate combines approximately 4–5 years of research (amounting to 3–5 scientific articles, some of which must be first-author) and 60 ECTS points of studies.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Other universities such as Aalto University award degrees such as *tekniikan tohtori* (*TkT*, engineering), *taiteen tohtori* (*TaT*, art), etc., which are translated in English to Doctor of Science (D.Sc.), and they are formally equivalent.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The licentiate (*filosofian lisensiaatti* or *FL*) requires only 2–3 years of research and is sometimes done before an FT.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] After 1984, only one type of doctoral degree remained, called "doctorate" (*Doctorat*).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Students pursuing the PhD degree must first complete a master's degree program, which takes two years after graduation with a bachelor's degree (five years in total).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The candidate must apply to a doctoral research project associated with a doctoral advisor (Directeur de thèse or directeur doctoral) with a habilitation throughout the doctoral program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The PhD admission is granted by a graduate school (in French, "école doctorale").
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A PhD candidate may follow some in-service training offered by the graduate school while continuing their research in a laboratory.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Their research may be carried out in a laboratory, at a university or in a company.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In the first case, the candidates can be hired by the university or a research organisation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In the last case, the company hires the candidate and they are supervised by both the company's tutor and a lab's professor.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Completion of the PhD degree generally requires 3 years after the master's degree but it can last longer in specific cases.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The financing of PhD research comes mainly from funds for research of the French Ministry of Higher Education and Research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The most common procedure is a short-term employment contract called doctoral contract: the institution of higher education is the employer and the PhD candidate the employee.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] However, the candidate can apply for funds from a company, which can host them at its premises (as in the case where PhD candidates do their research at a company).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In another possible situation, the company and the institute can sign a funding agreement together so that the candidate still has a public doctoral contract but is works at the company on a daily basis (for example, this is particularly the case for the (French) Scientific Cooperation Foundation).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Many other resources come from some regional/city projects, some associations, etc.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In Germany, admission to a doctoral program is generally on the basis of having an advanced degree (i.e., a master's degree, *diplom*, *magister*, or *staatsexamen*), mostly in a related field and having above-average grades.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A candidate must also find a tenured professor from a university to serve as the formal advisor and supervisor (*Betreuer*) of the dissertation throughout the doctoral program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] This supervisor is informally referred to as *Doktorvater* or *Doktormutter*, which literally translate to "doctor's father" and "doctor's mother" respectively.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The formal admission is the beginning of the so-called *Promotionsverfahren*, while the final granting of the degree is called *Promotion*.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The duration of the doctorate depends on the field.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] A doctorate in medicine may take less than a full-time year to complete; those in other fields, two to six years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Most doctorates are awarded with specific Latin designations for the field of research (except for engineering, where the designation is German), instead of a general name for all fields (such as the PhD).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Over fifty such designations exist, many of them rare or no longer in use.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] As a title, the degree is commonly written in front of the name in abbreviated form, e.g., *Dr. rer. nat.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Max Mustermann*, dropping the designation entirely.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] However, leaving out the designation is only allowed when the doctoral degree is not an honorary doctorate, which must be indicated by *Dr. h.c.* (from Latin honoris causa).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] While most German doctorates are considered equivalent to the PhD, an exception is the medical doctorate, where "doctoral" dissertations are often written alongside undergraduate study.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The European Research Council decided in 2010 that those doctorates do not meet the international standards of a PhD research degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] There are different forms of university-level institution in Germany, but only professors from "Universities" (Univ.-Prof.) can serve as doctoral supervisors – "Universities of Applied Sciences" (Fachhochschulen) are not entitled to award doctorates, although some exceptions apply to this rule.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Depending on the university, doctoral students (*Doktoranden*) can be required to attend formal classes or lectures, some of them also including exams or other scientific assignments, in order to get one or more certificates of qualification (*Qualifikationsnachweise*).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Depending on the doctoral regulations (*Promotionsordnung*) of the university and sometimes on the status of the doctoral student, such certificates may not be required.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Usually, former students, research assistants or lecturers from the same university, may be spared from attending extra classes.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Instead, under the tutelage of a single professor or advisory committee, they are expected to conduct independent research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In addition to doctoral studies, many doctoral candidates work as teaching assistants, research assistants, or lecturers.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Many universities have established research-intensive *Graduiertenkollegs* ("graduate colleges"), which are graduate schools that provide funding for doctoral studies.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The typical duration of a doctoral program can depend heavily on the subject and area of research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] Usually, three to five years of full-time research work are required.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] The average time to graduation is 4.5 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p02] In 2014, the median age of new PhD graduates was 30.4 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In India, a master's degree is usually required to gain admission to a doctoral program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Direct admission to a PhD program after graduating to BTech may also be granted by the IITs, the IIITs, the NITs, and the Academy of Scientific and Innovative Research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In some subjects, completing a Master of Philosophy (MPhil) is a prerequisite to obtaining funding/fellowship for a PhD.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] According to new rules prescribed by the UGC, universities must conduct Research Eligibility Tests in ability and the selected subject.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] After clearing these tests, the shortlisted candidates are required to appear for an interview with the available PhD supervisor and give presentations of their research proposal (plan of work or synopsis).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] During study, candidates must submit progress reports and after successful completion of the coursework, are required to give a pre-submission presentation and finally defend their thesis in an open defense viva-voce.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] It is mandatory in India to qualify for the National Eligibility Test to apply for a professorship, lectureship or Junior Research Fellowship (NET for LS and JRF) conducted by the National Testing Agency (NTA).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca* (research doctorate), abbreviated to "Dott.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Ric." or "PhD", is an academic title awarded at the end of a course of not less than three years, admission to which is based on entrance examinations and academic rankings in the Bachelor of Arts ("Laurea", a three-year diploma) and Master of Arts ("Laurea Magistrale" a two-year diploma).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] While the standard PhD follows the Bologna process, the MD–PhD programme may be completed in two years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The first institution in Italy to create a doctoral program (PhD) was Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa in 1927 under the historic name *"Diploma di Perfezionamento"*.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Further, the research doctorates or PhD (**Dottorato di ricerca**) in Italy were introduced by law and Presidential Decree in 1980, referring to the reform of academic teaching, training and experimentation in organisation and teaching methods.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Doctorate courses are open, without age or citizenship limits, to all those who already hold a "laurea magistrale" (master degree) or similar academic title awarded abroad which has been recognised as equivalent to an Italian degree by the Committee responsible for the entrance examinations.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The number of places on offer each year and details of the entrance examinations are set out in the examination announcement.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] *dr*) is an advanced academic degree awarded by universities in most fields and by the Polish Academy of Sciences, regulated by the Polish parliament acts and the government orders, in particular by the Ministry of Science and Higher Education of the Republic of Poland.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Students with a master's degree or equivalent are accepted to a doctoral entrance exam.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The title of PhD is awarded to a scientist who has completed a minimum of three years of PhD studies (Pol.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] *studia doktoranckie*; not required to obtain PhD), finished a theoretical or laboratory scientific work, passed all PhD examinations; submitted the dissertation, a document presenting the author's research and findings, and successfully defended the doctoral thesis.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Typically, upon completion, the candidate undergoes an oral examination, always public, by a supervisory committee with expertise in the given discipline.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The doctorate was introduced in Sweden in 1477 and in Denmark–Norway in 1479 and awarded in theology, law, and medicine, while the magister's degree was the highest degree at the Faculty of Philosophy, equivalent to the doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Scandinavian countries were among the early adopters of a degree known as a doctorate of philosophy, based upon the German model.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Denmark and Norway both introduced the Dr.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Phil(os). degree in 1824, replacing the Magister's degree as the highest degree, while Uppsala University of Sweden renamed its Magister's degree *Filosofie Doktor* (fil. dr) in 1863.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These degrees, however, became comparable to the German Habilitation rather than the doctorate, as Scandinavian countries did not have a separate Habilitation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The degrees were uncommon and not a prerequisite for employment as a professor; rather, they were seen as distinctions similar to the British (higher) doctorates (DLitt, DSc).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Today, the Norwegian PhD degree is awarded to candidates who have completed a supervised doctoral programme at an institution, while candidates with a master's degree who have conducted research on their own may submit their work for a Dr.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Philos. defence at a relevant institution.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] PhD candidates must complete one trial lecture before they can defend their thesis, whereas Dr.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Philos. candidates must complete two trial lectures.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In Sweden, the doctorate of philosophy was introduced at Uppsala University's Faculty of Philosophy in 1863.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In Sweden, the Latin term is officially translated into Swedish *filosofie doktor* and commonly abbreviated fil. dr or FD.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The degree represents the traditional Faculty of Philosophy and encompasses subjects from biology, physics, and chemistry, to languages, history, and social sciences, being the highest degree in these disciplines.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Sweden currently has two research-level degrees, the Licentiate's degree, which is comparable to the Danish degree formerly known as the Licentiate's degree and now as the ph.d., and the higher doctorate of philosophy, *Filosofie Doktor*.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Some universities in Sweden also use the term *teknologie doktor* for doctorates awarded by institutes of technology (for doctorates in engineering or natural science related subjects such as materials science, molecular biology, computer science etc.).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The Swedish term fil. dr is often also used as a translation of corresponding degrees from e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Singapore has six universities offering doctoral study opportunities: National University of Singapore, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore Management University, Singapore Institute of Technology, Singapore University of Technology and Design, and Singapore University of Social Sciences.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The first doctoral degree in South Africa was issued in 1899 by the University of the Cape of Good Hope (now University of South Africa or UNISA) and the first PhDs were conferred in the 1920s by the University of Cape Town and the University of the Witwatersrand.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Owing to the influence of British colonialism, South African higher education bears profound similarities to the modern UK universities system.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] South Africa boasts twenty-six state universities, all of which offer doctoral degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Presently, only two private institutions offer accredited PhDs, including the South African Theological Seminary and St.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Typically, South African colleges and universities abbreviate Doctor of Philosophy with either PhD or DPhil.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] South African PhD programs require both a four-year undergraduate and a relevant graduate degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Certain PhD programs require preexisting knowledge of research languages or field experience.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Some programs require applicants undergo an interview or provide references, a curriculum vitae, and letters of recommendation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Typically, PhD applicants must furnish a provisional research proposal which discloses the basic trajectory of their area of interest.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] English competency is a universal requirement.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Akin to PhD programs in the UK and in the Netherlands, South African PhD programs consist of a research thesis or dissertation produced under the supervision of a subject-matter expert.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] South African PhD programs are designed to result in a substantial piece of scholarship that has undergone critical evaluation through peer review.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Unlike PhD programs in many other African countries or the US, South African PhD programs rarely involve coursework and are undertaken through rigorous and semi-independent research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Most South African PhD programs are designed to be completed within three to six years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In Spain, doctoral degrees are regulated by *Real Decreto* (Royal Decree in Spanish) 99/2011 from the 2014/2015 academic year.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] They are granted by a university on behalf of the King, and its diploma has the force of a public document.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The Ministry of Science keeps a National Registry of Theses called TESEO.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] All doctoral programs are of a research nature.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The studies should include original results and can take a maximum of three years, although this period can be extended under certain circumstances to 5 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The student must write their thesis presenting a new discovery or original contribution to science.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] If approved by her or his "thesis director (or directors)", the study will be presented to a panel of 3–5 distinguished scholars.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Any doctor attending the public presentations is allowed to challenge the candidate with questions on their research.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] If approved, they will receive the doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Four marks can be granted: Unsatisfactory, Pass, Satisfactory, and Excellent.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] "Cum laude" (with all honours, in Latin) denomination can be added to the Excellent ones if all five members of the tribunal agree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The social standing of doctors in Spain was evidenced by the fact that Philip III let PhD holders to take seat and cover their heads during an act in the University of Salamanca in which the King took part so as to recognise their merits.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] This right to cover their heads in the presence of the King is traditionally reserved in Spain to Grandees and Dukes.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The concession is remembered in solemn ceremonies held by the university by telling Doctors to take seat and cover their heads as a reminder of that royal leave.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] All Doctor Degree holders are reciprocally recognized as equivalent in Germany and Spain ("Bonn Agreement of November 14, 1994").
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In Ukraine, starting in 2016, in Ukraine Doctor of Philosophy (PhD, Ukrainian: Доктор філософії) is the highest education level and the first science degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] PhD is awarded in recognition of a substantial contribution to scientific knowledge, origination of new directions and visions in science.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] A PhD degree is a prerequisite for heading a university department in Ukraine.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Upon completion of a PhD, a PhD holder can elect to continue their studies and get a post-doctoral degree called "Doctor of Sciences" (DSc.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Ukrainian: Доктор наук), which is the second and the highest science degree in Ukraine.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] For example, the University of Edinburgh requires a minimum of a 2:1 honours degree (or international equivalent) for a PhD in clinical psychology, while its business school requires a master's degree with an average of 65% in the taught components and a distinction-level dissertation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] For students who are not from English-speaking countries, UK Visas and Immigration requires universities to assess English proficiency.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Many do this using IELTS tests, although the requirements may vary depending on the institution.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] 143 UK universities require applicants to undergo IELTS before admission, with minimum acceptable scores ranging from 4 to 6.5 and above.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] However, some universities are willing to accept students without IELTS.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Students are first accepted onto an MPhil or MRes programme and may transfer to PhD regulations upon satisfactory progress, this is sometimes referred to as APG (Advanced Postgraduate) status.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] This is typically done after one or two years and the research work done may count towards the PhD degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] If a student fails to make satisfactory progress, they may be offered the opportunity to write up and submit for an MPhil degree, e.g. at King's College London and the University of Manchester.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In many universities, the MPhil is also offered as a stand-alone research degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] This requirement was introduced in 2007 due to concerns about overseas terrorism and weapons proliferation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In the United Kingdom, funding for PhD students is sometimes provided by government-funded Research Councils (UK Research and Innovation – UKRI) or the European Social Fund, usually in the form of a tax-free bursary which consists of tuition fees together with a stipend.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Higher fees are often charged for laboratory-based degrees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] As of 2022/23, the national minimum stipend for UKRI-funded students is £16,062 per year, increasing annually typically with inflation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] PhD work beyond this may be unfunded or funded from other sources.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] A very small number of scientific studentships are sometimes paid at a higher rate – for example, in London, Cancer Research UK, the ICR and the Wellcome Trust stipend rates start at around £19,000 and progress annually to around £23,000 a year; an amount that is tax and national insurance free.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Research Council funding is distributed to Doctoral Training Partnerships and Centres for Doctoral Training, who are responsible for student selection, within the eligibility guidelines established by the Research Councils.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The ESRC (Economic and Social Science Research Council), for example, explicitly state that a 2.1 minimum (or a master's degree) is required.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Many students who are not in receipt of external funding may choose to undertake the degree part-time, thus reducing the tuition fees.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The tuition fee per annum for part-time PhD degrees are typically 50–60% of the equivalent full-time doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] However, since the duration of a part-time PhD degree is longer than a full-time degree, the overall cost may be the same or higher.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The part-time PhD degree option provides free time in which to earn money for subsistence.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Students may also take part in tutoring, work as research assistants, or (occasionally) deliver lectures, at a rate of typically £12–14 per hour, either to supplement existing low income or as a sole means of funding.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] There is usually a preliminary assessment to remain in the program and the thesis is submitted at the end of a three- to four-year program.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These periods are usually extended *pro rata* for part-time students.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] With special dispensation, the final date for the thesis can sometimes be extended for additional years, for a total of up to six or seven.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] For full-time PhDs, a four-year time limit has now been fixed and students must apply for an extension to submit a thesis past this point.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Since the early 1990s, British funding councils have adopted a policy of penalising departments where large proportions of students fail to submit their theses in four years after achieving PhD-student status (or pro rata equivalent) by reducing the number of funded places in subsequent years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Furthermore, supervising staff are encouraged in their career progression to ensure that the PhD students under their supervision finalise the projects in three rather than the four years that the program is permitted to cover.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These issues contribute to an overall discrepancy between supervisors and PhD candidates in the priority they assign to the quality and impact of the research contained in a PhD project.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] There has recently been an increase in the number of Integrated PhD programs available, such as at the University of Southampton.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These courses include a Master of Research (MRes) in the first year, which consists of a taught component as well as laboratory rotation projects.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The PhD must then be completed within the next three years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] As this includes the MRes all deadlines and timeframes are brought forward to encourage completion of both MRes and PhD within four years from commencement.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These programs are designed to provide students with a greater range of skills than a standard PhD, and for the university, they are a means of gaining an extra years' fees from public sources.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Oxford) abbreviate their Doctor of Philosophy degree as "DPhil", while most use the abbreviation "PhD"; but these are stylistic conventions, and the degrees are in all other respects equivalent.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] However, some UK universities still maintain the option of submitting a thesis for the award of a higher doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Recent years have seen the introduction of professional doctorates, which are the same level as PhDs but more specific in their field.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Most tend not to be solely academic, but combine academic research, a taught component or a professional qualification.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] A more generic degree also used is DProf or ProfD.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These typically have a more formal taught component consisting of smaller research projects, as well as a 40,000–60,000-word thesis component, which together are officially considered equivalent to a PhD degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In the United States, the PhD degree is the highest academic degree awarded by universities in most fields of study.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] There are more than 282 universities in the United States that award the PhD degree, and those universities vary widely in their criteria for admission, as well as the rigor of their academic programs.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Depending on the specific field of study, completion of a PhD program usually takes four to eight years of study after the bachelor's degree; those students who begin a PhD program with a master's degree may complete their PhD degree a year or two sooner.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] As PhD programs typically lack the formal structure of undergraduate education, there are significant individual differences in the time taken to complete the degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Overall, 57% of students who begin a PhD program in the US will complete their degree within ten years, approximately 30% will drop out or be dismissed, and the remaining 13% of students will continue on past ten years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The median age of PhD recipients in the US is 32 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] While many candidates are awarded their degree in their 20s, 6% of PhD recipients in the US are older than 45 years.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The **number of PhD diplomas** awarded by US universities has risen nearly every year since 1957, according to data compiled by the US National Science Foundation.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] PhD students at US universities typically receive a tuition waiver and some form of annual stipend.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Many US PhD students work as teaching assistants or research assistants.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Sometimes graduate schools encourage their students to seek outside funding; many are supported by fellowships they obtain for themselves or by their advisers' research grants from government agencies such as the National Science Foundation and the National Institutes of Health.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Many Ivy League and other well-endowed universities provide funding for the entire duration of the degree program or for most of it, especially in the forms of tuition waivers/stipends.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The Russian degree of Candidate of Sciences is also officially recognised by the Government of the French Republic as equivalent to French doctorate.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] According to the International Standard Classification of Education, for purposes of international educational statistics, Candidate of Sciences belongs to ISCED level 8, or "doctoral or equivalent", together with PhD, DPhil, DLitt, DSc, LLD, Doctorate, or similar.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] It is mentioned in the Russian version of ISCED 2011 (par.262) on the UNESCO website as an equivalent to PhD belonging to this level.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] In the same way as PhD degrees awarded in many English-speaking countries, Candidate of Sciences allows its holders to reach the level of the Docent.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] It constitutes a higher qualification compared to PhD as against the European Qualifications Framework (EQF) or Dublin Descriptors.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] About 88% of Russian students studying at state universities study at the expense of budget funds.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The average stipend in Russia (as of August 2011) is $430 a year ($35/month).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] The average tuition fee in graduate school is $2,000 per year.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] On 19 June 2013, for the first time in the Russian Federation, defenses were held for the PhD degree awarded by universities, instead of the Candidate of Sciences degree awarded by the State Supreme Certification Commission.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Renat Yuldashev, the graduate of the Department of Applied Cybernetics of the Faculty of Mathematics and Mechanics of St.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Petersburg State University, was the first to defend his thesis in field of mathematics according to new rules for the PhD SPbSU degree.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] For the defense procedure in the field of mathematics, it was used the experience of joint Finnish-Russian research and educational program organized in 2007 by the Faculty of Information Technology of the University of Jyväskylä and the Faculty of Mathematics and Mechanics of St.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Petersburg State University: co-chairs of the program — N.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Neittaanmäki, were organizers of the first defenses and co-supervisors of dissertations.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] At some universities, there may be training for those wishing to supervise PhD studies.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] There is much literature available, such as Delamont, Atkinson, and Parry (1997).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Dinham and Scott (2001) have argued that the worldwide growth in research students has been matched by the increase in the number of what they term "how-to" texts for both students and supervisors, citing examples such as Pugh and Phillips (1987).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These authors report empirical data on the benefits to a PhD candidate from publishing; students are more likely to publish with adequate encouragement from their supervisors.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Wisker (2005) has reported that research into this field distinguishes two models of supervision: The technical-rationality model of supervision, emphasising technique; and the negotiated order model, which is less mechanistic, emphasising fluid and dynamic change in the PhD process.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] These two models were first distinguished by Acker, Hill and Black (1994; cited in Wisker, 2005).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Considerable literature exists on the expectations that supervisors may have of their students (Phillips & Pugh, 1987) and the expectations that students may have of their supervisors (Phillips & Pugh, 1987; Wilkinson, 2005) in the course of PhD supervision.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Similar expectations are implied by the Quality Assurance Agency's Code for Supervision (Quality Assurance Agency, 1999; cited in Wilkinson, 2005).
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] PhD graduates represent a relatively small, elite group within most countries — around 1.1% of adults among OECD countries.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Slovenia, Switzerland and Luxembourg have higher numbers of PhD Graduates per capita as illustrated here.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] For Slovenia, this is because MSc degrees before Bologna Process are ranked at the same level of education as PhD.
[src:sotaro-kita/doctor-of-philosophy-p03] Without the MSc, Slovenia has 1.4% PhD graduates, which is comparable to the average in OECD and EU-23 countries.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A **gesture** is a form of nonverbal communication or non-vocal communication in which visible bodily actions communicate particular messages, either in place of, or in conjunction with, speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures differ from physical non-verbal communication that does not communicate specific messages, such as purely expressive displays, proxemics, or displays of joint attention.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures allow individuals to communicate a variety of feelings and thoughts, from contempt and hostility to approval and affection, often together with body language in addition to words when they speak.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gesticulation and speech work independently of each other, but join to provide emphasis and meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gesture processing takes place in areas of the brain such as Broca's and Wernicke's areas, which are used by speech and sign language.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In fact, language is thought by some scholars to have evolved in *Homo sapiens* from an earlier system consisting of manual gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The theory that language evolved from manual gestures, termed Gestural Theory, dates back to the work of 18th-century philosopher and priest Abbé de Condillac, and has been revived by contemporary anthropologist Gordon W.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Hewes, in 1973, as part of a discussion on the origin of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures have been studied throughout time from different philosophers.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Marcus Fabius Quintilianus was a Roman Rhetorician who studied in his Institutio Oratoria on how gesture can be used on rhetorical discourses.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] One of his greatest works and foundation for communication was the "Institutio Oratoria" where he explains his observations and nature of different oratories.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A study done in 1644, by John Bulwer an English physician and early Baconian natural philosopher wrote five works exploring human communications pertaining to gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Bulwer analyzed dozens of gestures and provided a guide under his book named Chirologia which focused on hand gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In the 19th century, Andrea De Jorio an Italian antiquarian who considered a lot of research about body language published an extensive account of gesture expressions.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Meltzoff an American psychologist internationally renown for infant and child development conducted a study in 1977 on the imitation of facial and manual gestures by newborns.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The study concluded that "infants between 12 and 21 days of age can imitate the facial and manual gestures of parents".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A peer-reviewed journal Gesture has been published since 2001, and was founded by Adam Kendon and Cornelia Müller.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The International Society for Gesture Studies (ISGS) was founded in 2002.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gesture has frequently been taken up by researchers in the field of dance studies and performance studies in ways that emphasize the ways they are culturally and contextually inflected.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Performance scholar Carrie Noland describes gestures as "learned techniques of the body" and stresses the way gestures are embodied corporeal forms of cultural communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] But rather than just residing within one cultural context, she describes how gestures migrate across bodies and locations to create new cultural meanings and associations.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] She also posits how they might function as a form of "resistance to homogenization" because they are so dependent on the specification of the bodies that perform them.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gesture has also been taken up within queer theory, ethnic studies and their intersections in performance studies, as a way to think about how the moving body gains social meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] José Esteban Muñoz uses the idea of gesture to mark a kind of refusal of finitude and certainty and links gesture to his ideas of ephemera.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Muñoz specifically draws on the African-American dancer and drag queen performer Kevin Aviance to articulate his interest not in what queer gestures might mean, but what they might perform.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Juana María Rodríguez borrows ideas of phenomenology and draws on Noland and Muñoz to investigate how gesture functions in queer sexual practices as a way to rewrite gender and negotiate power relations.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] She also connects gesture to Giorgio Agamben's idea of "means without ends" to think about political projects of social justice that are incomplete, partial, and legibile within culturally and socially defined spheres of meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Since the late 1990s, most research has revolved around the contrasting hypothesis that Lexical gestures serve a primarily cognitive purpose in aiding the process of speech production.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] As of 2012, there is research to suggest that Lexical Gesture does indeed serve a primarily communicative purpose and cognitive only secondary, but in the realm of socio-pragmatic communication, rather than lexico-semantic modification.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Humans have the ability to communicate through language, but they can also express through gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In particular, gestures can be transmitted through movements of body parts, face, and body expressions.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Researchers Goldin Meadow and Brentari D. conducted research in 2015 and concluded that communicating through sign language is no different from spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The first way to distinguish between categories of gesture is to differentiate between communicative gesture and informative gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] While most gestures can be defined as possibly happening during the course of spoken utterances, the informative-communicative dichotomy focuses on intentionality of meaning and communication in co-speech gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Informative gestures are passive gestures that provide information about the speaker as a person and not about what the speaker is trying to communicate.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Some movements are not purely considered gestures, however a person could perform these adapters in such way like scratching, adjusting clothing, and tapping.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These gestures can occur during speech, but they may also occur independently of communication, as they are not a part of active communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] While informative gestures may communicate information about the person speaking (e.g. itchy, uncomfortable, etc.), this communication is not engaged with any language being produced by the person gesturing.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Army recruitment poster of Uncle Sam, he is pointing and sending a non-verbal form of gesture by implying he wants the viewer to join the U.S.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This is a form of symbolic gesture, usually used in the absence of speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Body language is a form of nonverbal communication that allows visual cues that transmit messages without speaking.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are movement that are made with the body: arms, hands, facial, etc.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Barbara and Allan Pease, authors of *The Definitive Book of Body Language*, concluded that everyone does a shoulder shrug, a gesture signifying that the person is not comprehending what they are supposed to be understanding.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Also, that showing the palms of both hands to show a person is not hiding anything, and raising the eyebrows to indicate a greeting.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Finger gestures are commonly used in a variety of ways, from point at something to indicate that you want to show a person something to indicating a thumbs up to show everything is good.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Some gestures are near universals, i.e., found all over the world with only some exceptions.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] An example is the head shake to signify "no".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Also, in most cultures nodding your head signifies "Yes", which the book "The Definitive Book of Body Language" describes as submissive gesture to representing the conversation is going the direction of the person speaking.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The book explains that people who are born deaf can show a form of submissive gesture to signify "Yes".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Within the realm of communicative gestures, the first distinction to be made is between gestures made with the hands and arms, and gestures made with other parts of the body.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Examples of Non-manual gestures may include head nodding and shaking, shoulder shrugging, and facial expression, among others.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Non-manual gestures are attested in languages all around the world, but have not been the primary focus of most research regarding co-speech gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A gesture that is a form of communication in which bodily actions communicate particular messages.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The most familiar are the so-called emblems or quotable gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These are conventional, culture-specific gestures that can be used as replacement for words, such as the handwave used in the US for "hello" and "goodbye".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A single emblematic gesture can have a very different significance in different cultural contexts, ranging from complimentary to highly offensive.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The page List of gestures discusses emblematic gestures made with one hand, two hands, hand and other body parts, and body and facial gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Symbolic gestures can occur either concurrently or independently of vocal speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Symbolic gestures are iconic gestures that are widely recognized, fixed, and have conventionalized meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Deictic gestures can occur simultaneously with vocal speech or in place of it.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Deictic gestures are gestures that consist of indicative or pointing motions.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These gestures often work in the same way as demonstrative words and pronouns like "this" or "that".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Deictic gestures can refer to concrete or intangible objects or people.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Motor or beat gestures usually consist of short, repetitive, rhythmic movements that are closely tied with prosody in verbal speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Unlike symbolic and deictic gestures, beat gestures cannot occur independently of verbal speech and convey no semantic information.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] For example, some people wave their hands as they speak to emphasize a certain word or phrase.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These gestures are closely coordinated with speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The so-called beat gestures are used in conjunction with speech and keep time with the rhythm of speech to emphasize certain words or phrases.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These types of gestures are integrally connected to speech and thought processes.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Other spontaneous gestures used during speech production known as iconic gestures are more full of content, and may echo, or elaborate, the meaning of the co-occurring speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] They depict aspects of spatial images, actions, people, or objects.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] For example, a gesture that depicts the act of throwing may be synchronous with the utterance, "He threw the ball right into the window." Such gestures that are used along with speech tend to be universal.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] For example, one describing that they are feeling cold due to a lack of proper clothing and/or a cold weather can accompany their verbal description with a visual one.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This can be achieved through various gestures such as by demonstrating a shiver and/or by rubbing the hands together.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The elaboration of lexical gestures falls on a spectrum of iconic-metaphorical in how closely tied they are to the lexico-semantic content of the verbal speech they coordinate with.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Lexical gestures, like motor gestures, cannot occur independently of verbal speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The purpose of lexical gestures is still widely contested in the literature with some linguists arguing that lexical gestures serve to amplify or modulate the semantic content of lexical speech, or that it serves a cognitive purpose in aiding in lexical access and retrieval or verbal working memory.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Most recent research suggests that lexical gestures serve a primarily socio-pragmatic role.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Studies affirm a strong link between gesture typology and language development.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Young children under the age of two seem to rely on pointing gestures to refer to objects that they do not know the names of.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Once the words are learned, they eschewed those referential (pointing) gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] One would think that the use of gesture would decrease as the child develops spoken language, but results reveal that gesture frequency increased as speaking frequency increased with age.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] There is, however, a change in gesture typology at different ages, suggesting a connection between gestures and language development.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Children most often use pointing and adults rely more on iconic and beat gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] As children begin producing sentence-like utterances, they also begin producing new kinds of gestures that adults use when speaking (iconics and beats).
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Evidence of this systematic organization of gesture is indicative of its association to language development.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestural languages such as American Sign Language operate as complete natural languages that are gestural in modality.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] They should not be confused with finger spelling, in which a set of emblematic gestures are used to represent a written alphabet.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Sign languages are different from gesturing in that concepts are modeled by certain hand motions or expressions and has a specific established structure while gesturing is more malleable and has no specific structure rather it supplements speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Before an established sign language was created in Nicaragua after the 1970s, deaf Nicaraguans would use "home signs" in order to communicate with others.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] These home signs were not part of a unified language but were still used as familiar motions and expressions used within their family—still closely related to language rather than gestures with no specific structure.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Home signs are similar to the gestural actions of chimpanzees.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are used by these animals in place of verbal language, which is restricted in animals due to their lacking certain physiological and articulation abilities that humans have for speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The function of gestures may have been a significant player in the evolution of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gesturing is probably universal; there has been no report of a community that does not gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are a crucial part of everyday conversation such as chatting, describing a route, negotiating prices on a market; they are ubiquitous.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are learned embodied cultural practices that can function as a way to interpret ethnic, gender, and sexual identity.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures, commonly referred to as "body language", play an important role in industry.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Proper body language etiquette in business dealings can be crucial for success.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] However, gestures can have different meanings according to the country in which they are expressed.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In an age of global business, diplomatic cultural sensitivity has become a necessity.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures that we take as innocent may be seen by someone else as deeply insulting.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are also a means to initiate a mating ritual.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This may include elaborate dances and other movements.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures play a major role in many aspects of human life.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Additionally, when people use gestures, there is a certain shared background knowledge.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Different cultures use similar gestures when talking about a specific action such as how we gesture the idea of drinking out of a cup.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] When an individual makes a gesture, another person can understand because of recognition of the actions/shapes.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures have been documented in the arts such as in Greek vase paintings, Indian Miniatures or European paintings.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures play a central role in religious or spiritual rituals.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In Hinduism and Buddhism, a *mudra* (Sanskrit, literally "seal", "gesture" or "attitude") is a symbolic gesture made with the hand, body or mind.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Each mudra has a specific meaning, and is associated with a specific spiritual quality or state.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In yoga, mudras are considered to be higher practices which lead to awakening of the pranas, chakras and kundalini, and which can bestow major siddhis, psychic powers, on the advanced practitioner.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In Hindu and Buddhist iconography mudras play a central role.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] For example, Vitarka Vicara, the gesture of discussion and transmission of Buddhist teaching, is done by joining the tips of the thumb and the index together, while keeping the other fingers straight.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] A common Christian religious gesture is crossing oneself as a sign of respect, also known as making the sign of the cross; often this is accompanied by kneeling before a sacred object.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In the renewal of the Catholic liturgy promoted by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s, "actions, gestures, and bodily attitudes" were noted as means by which a whole worshipping community could participate in the liturgical action.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are processed in the same areas of the brain as speech and sign language such as the left inferior frontal gyrus (Broca's area) and the posterior middle temporal gyrus, posterior superior temporal sulcus and superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke's area).
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] It has been suggested that these parts of the brain originally supported the pairing of gesture and meaning and then were adapted in human evolution "for the comparable pairing of sound and meaning as voluntary control over the vocal apparatus was established and spoken language evolved".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] As a result, it underlies both symbolic gesture and spoken language in the present human brain.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Their common neurological basis also supports the idea that symbolic gesture and spoken language are two parts of a single fundamental semiotic system that underlies human discourse.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The linkage of hand and body gestures in conjunction with speech is further revealed by the nature of gesture use in blind individuals during conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This phenomenon uncovers a function of gesture that goes beyond portraying communicative content of language and extends David McNeill's view of the gesture-speech system.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This suggests that gesture and speech work tightly together, and a disruption of one (speech or gesture) will cause a problem in the other.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Studies have found strong evidence that speech and gesture are innately linked in the brain and work in an efficiently wired and choreographed system.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] McNeill's view of this linkage in the brain is just one of three currently up for debate; the others declaring gesture to be a "support system" of spoken language or a physical mechanism for lexical retrieval.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Because of this connection of co-speech gestures—a form of manual action—in language in the brain, Roel Willems and Peter Hagoort conclude that both gestures and language contribute to the understanding and decoding of a speaker's encoded message.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Because gestures aided in understanding the relayed message, there was not as great a need for semantic selection or control that would otherwise be required of the listener through Broca's area.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures are a way to represent the thoughts of an individual, which are prompted in working memory.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The researchers found that those with low capacity of working memory who were able to use gestures actually recalled more terms than those with low capacity who were not able to use gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The movement of gestures can be used to interact with technology like computers, using touch or multi-touch popularised by the iPhone, physical movement detection and visual motion capture, used in video game consoles.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] It can be recorded using kinematic methodology.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] In order to better understand the linguistic values that gestures hold, Adam Kendon, a pioneer in gesture research has proposed to look at it as a continuum from less linguistic to fully linguistic.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Using the continuum, speech declines as "the language-like properties of gestural behaviors increase and idiosyncratic gestures are replaced by socially regulated signs".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Gestures of different kinds fall within this continuum and include spontaneous gesticulations, language-like gestures, pantomime, emblems, and sign language.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Spontaneous gesticulations are not evident without the presence of speech, assisting in the process of vocalization, whereas language-like gestures are "iconic and metaphoric, but lack consistency and are context-dependent".
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] "Language-like gesture" implies that the gesture is assuming something linguistic (Loncke, 2013).
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Pantomime falls in the middle of the continuum and requires shared conventions.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] This kind of gesture helps convey information or describe an event.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] Following pantomime are emblems, which have specific meanings to denote "feelings, obscenities, and insults" and are not required to be used in conjunction with speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/gesture] The most linguistic gesture on Kendon's continuum is sign language, where "single manual signs have specific meanings and are combined with other manual signs according to specific rules".
[src:sotaro-kita/john-benjamins] John Benjamins is especially noted for its publications in language, linguistics, translation studies, political linguistics and literary studies.
[src:sotaro-kita/john-benjamins] John Benjamins publishes in print as well as online.
[src:sotaro-kita/john-benjamins] John Benjamins Publishing Company is a member of these professional and trade organizations: STM Association, ALPSP, UKSG, Mediafederatie-MEVW, CrossRef.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children develop receptive language abilities before their verbal or expressive language develops.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Receptive language (language perception) enables internal processing and understanding of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] For instance, six-month-old infants understand the meaning of basic words (such as banana or hand).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Expressive language (language production) is considered to begin with a stage of pre-verbal communication in which infants use gestures and vocalizations to make their intents known to others.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] According to a general principle of development, new forms then take over old functions, so that children learn words to express the same communicative functions they had already expressed by proverbial means.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children learn syntax through imitation, instruction, and reinforcement.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Language development is thought to proceed by ordinary processes of learning in which children acquire the forms, meanings, and uses of words and utterances from the linguistic input.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children often begin reproducing the words that they are repetitively exposed to.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The method in which we develop language skills is universal; however, the major debate is how the rules of syntax are acquired.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] There are two quite separate major theories of syntactic development: an empiricist account by which children learn all syntactic rules from the linguistic input, and a nativist approach by which some principles of syntax are innate and are transmitted through the human genome.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The nativist theory, proposed by Noam Chomsky, argues that language is a unique human accomplishment, and can be attributed to either "millions of years of evolution" or to "principles of neural organization that may be even more deeply grounded in physical law".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Chomsky says that all children have what is called an innate language acquisition device (LAD).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Theoretically, the LAD is an area of the brain that has a set of universal syntactic rules for all languages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This device provides children with the ability to make sense of knowledge and construct novel sentences with minimal external input and little experience.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Chomsky's claim is based upon the view that what children hear—their linguistic input—is insufficient to explain how they come to learn language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] He argues that linguistic input from the environment is limited and full of errors.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Therefore, nativists assume that it is impossible for children to learn linguistic information solely from their environment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] However, because children possess this LAD, they are in fact, able to learn language despite incomplete information from their environment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Their capacity to learn language is also attributed to the theory of universal grammar (UG), which posits that a certain set of structural rules are innate to humans, independent of sensory experience.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This view has dominated linguistic theory for over fifty years and remains highly influential, as witnessed by the number of articles in journals and books.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The empiricist theory suggests, contra Chomsky, that there is enough information in the linguistic input children receive and therefore, there is no need to assume an innate language acquisition device exists (see above).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Rather than a LAD evolved specifically for language, empiricists believe that general brain processes are sufficient for language acquisition.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] During this process, it is necessary for the child to actively engage with their environment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] For a child to learn language, the parent or caregiver adopts a particular way of appropriately communicating with the child; this is known as child-directed speech (CDS).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] CDS is used so that children are given the necessary linguistic information needed for their language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Empiricism is a general approach and sometimes goes along with the interactionist approach.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Statistical language acquisition, which falls under empiricist theory, suggests that infants acquire language by means of pattern perception.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Other researchers embrace an interactionist perspective, consisting of social-interactionist theories of language development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In such approaches, children learn language in the interactive and communicative context, learning language forms for meaningful moves of communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] These theories focus mainly on the caregiver's attitudes and attentiveness to their children in order to promote productive language habits.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] An older empiricist theory, the behaviorist theory proposed by B.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Skinner suggested that language is learned through operant conditioning, namely, by imitation of stimuli and by reinforcement of correct responses.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This perspective has not been widely accepted at any time, but by some accounts, is experiencing a resurgence.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] New studies use this theory now to treat individuals diagnosed with autism spectrum disorders.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Additionally, relational frame theory is growing from the behaviorist theory, which is important for acceptance and commitment therapy.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Some empiricist theory accounts today use behaviorist models.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Evolutionary biologists are skeptical of the claim that syntactic knowledge is transmitted in the human genome.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] However, many researchers claim that the ability to acquire such a complicated system is unique to the human species.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Non-biologists also tend to believe that our ability to learn spoken language may have been developed through the evolutionary process and that the foundation for language may be passed down genetically.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The ability to speak and understand human language requires speech production skills and abilities as well as multisensory integration of sensory processing abilities.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Scientists have conducted extensive research to see if other animal species are capable of learning a complex human language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Several studies have worked with great apes, owing to their close evolutionary relationship to humans.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In the documentary Project Nim, for example, researcher Herbert S.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Terrace conducted the study to nurture a young chimpanzee with intimate human interaction.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The researchers trained the chimp American Sign Language and treated it like a human child.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Finally, the chimp was able to learn over 114 signs to communicate his wants to the caregivers.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Unlike humans, however, Nim was unable to make use of significant grammar or context.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Other attempts to teach great apes language have met with varying degrees of success, and whether the communication the apes achieve can be equated to human language is controversial.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] One hotly debated issue is whether the biological contribution includes capacities specific to language acquisition, often referred to as universal grammar.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] For fifty years, linguist Noam Chomsky has argued for the hypothesis that children have innate, language-specific abilities that facilitate and constrain language learning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In particular, he has proposed that humans are biologically prewired to learn language at a certain time and in a certain way, arguing that children are born with a language acquisition device (LAD).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] However, since he developed the minimalist program, his latest version of theory of syntactic structure, Chomsky has reduced the elements of universal grammar, which he believes are prewired in humans to just the principle of recursion, thus voiding most of the nativist endeavor.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Researchers who believe that grammar is learned rather than innate, have hypothesized that language learning results from general cognitive abilities and the interaction between learners and their human interactants.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] According to this theory, the neural substrate for language results from a combination of the genetically determined complexity of the human brain and the 'functional validation of synapses' during the long period of postnatal maturation that is unique among primates.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Similarly, it has recently been suggested that the relatively slow development of the prefrontal cortex in humans may be one reason that humans are able to learn language, whereas other species are not.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Further research has indicated the influence of the FOXP2 gene.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] For a newborn, crying is the only means of communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Infants 1–5 months old have different tones of crying that indicate their emotions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Infants also begin laughing at this stage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] At 6–7 months old, infants begin to respond to their own name, yell and squeal, and distinguish emotions based on the tone of voice of the parent.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Between 7 and 10 months the infant starts putting words together, for example "mama" and "dada", but these words lack meaning and significance.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] communication begins at approximately 10–12 months, and the child starts to imitate any sounds they hear, for example animal sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The non-verbal communication of infants includes the use of gaze, head orientation and body positioning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Gestures are also widely used as an act of communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] All these stages can be delayed if the parents do not communicate with their infant on a daily basis.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] begins with the comprehension of parents and how they use it effectively in conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Infants are able to break down what adults and others are saying to them and use their comprehension of this communication to produce their own.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Verbal and nonverbal communication are both used at this stage of development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] At 12 months, children start to repeat the words they hear.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Adults, especially parents, are used as a point of reference for children in terms of the sound of words and what they mean in context of the conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children learn much of their verbal communication through repetition and observing others.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] If parents do not speak to their children at this age it can become quite difficult for them to learn the essentials of conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The vocabulary of a 1–2-year-old should consist of 50 words and can be up to 500.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Gestures that were used earlier on in development begin to be replaced by words and eventually are only used when needed.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Verbal communication is chosen over nonverbal as development progresses.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This creates a conversational structure that makes it easier for verbal communication to develop.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It also teaches patience, kindness, and respect as they learn from the direction of elders that one person should speak at a time.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children during this stage in their life also go through a recognition and continuity phase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children start to see that shared awareness is a factor in communication along with their development of symbolic direction of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This especially affects the relationship between the child and the caregiver; it is a crucial part of self-discovery for the child when they begin to take ownership over their own actions in a continuous manner.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In this age group children are still learning how to form abstract thoughts and are still communicating concretely.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children begin to be fluent in connecting sounds, syllables, and linking words that make sense together in one thought.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] They begin to participate in short conversations with others.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] can develop, generally resulting in slowed-down speech with a few letter enunciation errors (f, v, s, z).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] At the beginning of this stage toddlers tend to be missing function words and misunderstand how to use verb tenses.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Over time they start including functional words, pronouns, and auxiliary verbs.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This is the stage at which most children can pick up on emotional cues of the tone of adults' conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] If negative feedback is distinguished by the child, this ends with fear and avoidance of the associated verbal and nonverbal cues.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Toddlers develop the skills to listen and partially understand what another person is saying and can develop an appropriate response.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Much language development during this time period takes place in a school setting.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] At the beginning of the school age years, a child's vocabulary expands through exposure to reading, which also helps children to learn more difficult grammatical forms, including plurals and pronouns.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] which allows them to reflect and more clearly understand the language they use.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] They therefore start to understand jokes and riddles.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] and having confidence in complex word choices while talking with adults.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This is an important developmental stage socially and physiologically for the child.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] School-aged children can easily be influenced through communication and gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] As children continue to learn communication, they realize the difference between forms of intentions and understand that there are numerous different ways to express the same intent, with different meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] By the age of 10, the child's cognitive potential has matured and they can participate fully and understand the purpose of their conversations.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] During this time, the sophistication and effectiveness of communication skills increase and understanding of vocabulary and grammar increases as a result of education.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] go through changes in social interactions and cognitive development that influence the way they communicate.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] ), however, which can increase confusion and misunderstandings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] An individual's style of interpersonal communication depends on who they are communicating with.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Their relationships change influencing how they communicate with others.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] During this period, adolescents tend to communicate less with their parents and more with their friends.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When discussions are initiated in different channels of communication, attitude and predispositions are key factors that drive the individual to discuss their feelings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This also shows that respect in communication is a trait in interpersonal communication that is built on throughout development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The end of this adolescent stage is the basis for communication in the adult stage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Language development and processing begins before birth.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Evidence has shown that there is language development occurring antepartum.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] DeCasper and Spence performed a study in 1986 by having mothers read aloud during the last few weeks of pregnancy.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When the infants were born, they were then tested.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] They were read aloud a story while sucking on a pacifier; the story was either the story read by the mother when the infant was in utero or a new story.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The pacifier used was able to determine the rate of sucking that the infant was performing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When the story that the mother had read before was heard, the sucking of the pacifier was modified.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This did not occur during the story that the infant had not heard before.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The results for this experiment had shown that the infants were able to recognize what they had heard in utero, providing insight that language development had been occurring in the last six weeks of pregnancy.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Throughout the first year of life, infants are unable to communicate with language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Instead, infants communicate with gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This phenomenon is known as prelinguistic gestures, which are nonverbal ways that infants communicate that also had a plan backed with the gesture.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Examples of these could be pointing at an object, tugging on the shirt of a parent to get the parent's attention, etc.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Harding, 1983, devised the major criteria that come along with the behavior of prelinguistic gestures and their intent to communicate.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] There are three major criteria that go along with a prelinguistic gesture: waiting, persistence, and ultimately, development of alternative plans.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This process usually occurs around 8 months of age, where an appropriate scenario may be of a child tugging on the shirt of a parent to wait for the attention of the parent who would then notice the infant, which causes the infant to point to something they desire.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This would describe the first two criteria.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The development of alternative plans may arise if the parent does not acknowledge what the infant wants, the infant may entertain itself to satisfy the previous desire.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The way the parent responds to their child in this situation of "needing" and "wanting" will also result in the kind of attachment style their child will have.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When children reach about 15–18 months of age, language acquisition flourishes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] There is a surge in word production resulting from the growth of the cortex.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Infants begin to learn the words that form a sentence and within the sentence, the word endings can be interpreted.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Elissa Newport and colleagues (1999) found that humans learn first about the sounds of a language, and then move on to how to speak the language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This shows how infants learn the end of a word and know that a new word is being spoken.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] From this step, infants are then able to determine the structure of a language and word.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It appears that during the early years of language development females exhibit an advantage over males of the same age.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When infants between the age of 16 and 22 months were observed interacting with their mothers, a female advantage was obvious.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The females in this age range showed more spontaneous speech production than the males and this finding was not due to mothers speaking more with daughters than sons.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In addition, boys between 2 and 6 years as a group did not show higher performance in language development over their girl counterparts on experimental assessments.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In studies using adult populations, 18 and over, it seems that the female advantage may be task dependent.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Depending on the task provided, a female advantage may or may not be present.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Similarly, one study found that out of the 5.5% of American children with language impairments, 7.2% are male, and 3.8% are female.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] There are many different suggested explanations for this gender gap in language impairment prevalence.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It is currently believed that in regards to brain lateralization males are left-lateralized, while females are bilateralized.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Studies on patients with unilateral lesions have provided evidence that females are in fact more bilateralized with their verbal abilities.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It seems that when a female has experienced a lesion to the left hemisphere, she is better able to compensate for this damage than a male can.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] If a male has a lesion in the left hemisphere, his verbal abilities are greatly impaired in comparison to a control male of the same age without that damage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] However, these results may also be task-dependent as well as time-dependent.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Shriberg, Tomblin, and McSweeny (1999) suggest that the fine motor skills necessary for correct speech may develop more slowly in males.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This could explain why some of the language impairments in young males seem to spontaneously improve over time.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It is also suggested that the gender gap in language impairment prevalence could also be explained by the clinical over diagnosis of males.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Males tend to be clinically over diagnosed with a variety of disorders.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] A late 1990s study found that males were diagnosed with language impairment 1.5 times more than were females.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] (1999) further explains that this gap in the prevalence of language impairment could be because males tend to be more visible.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] These researchers reveal that male children tend to act out behaviorally when they have any sort of disorder, while female children tend to turn inward and develop emotional disorders as well.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Thus, the high ratio of males with language impairments may be connected with the fact that males are more visible, and thus more often diagnosed.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Research in writing development has been limited in psychology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In the research that has been conducted, focus has generally centred on the development of written and spoken language and their connection.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Spoken and written skills could be considered linked.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Researchers believe that children's spoken language influences their written language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When a child learns to write they need to master letter formation, spelling, punctuation and they also have to gain an understanding of the structure and the organisational patterns involved in written language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kroll's theory is one of the most significant on children's writing development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] He proposed that children's writing development is split into four phases.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kroll explicitly states that these phases are 'artificial' in the sense that the boundaries between the phases are imprecise and he recognises that each child is different, thus their development is unique.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The phases of writing development have been highlighted to give the reader a broad outline of what phases a child goes through during writing development; however when studying an individual's development in depth, the phases may be disregarded to an extent.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The first of Kroll's phases is the preparation for writing phase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In this phase the child is believed to grasp the technical skills needed for writing, allowing them to create the letters needed to write the words the children say.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In this initial phase children experience many opportunities to extend their spoken language skills.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Speaking and writing are considered fairly separate processes here, as children's writing is less well developed at this stage, whereas their spoken language is becoming more skilled.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kroll considers the second phase in writing development to be consolidation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Here, children begin to consolidate spoken and written language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In this phase children's writing skills rely heavily on their spoken language skills, and their written and spoken language becoming integrated.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children's written language skills become stronger as they use their spoken language skills to improve their writing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Then in turn, when a development in children's written language skills is seen, their spoken language skills have also improved.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] A child's written language in this phase mirrors their spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In the third phase, differentiation, children begin to learn that written language regularly differs in structure and style from spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The growth from consolidation to differentiation can be challenging for some children to grasp.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children can 'struggle with the transformation from the basically overt language of speech to the essentially covert activity of writing'.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] In this phase, the child learns that writing is generally considered more formal than spoken language, which is thought to be casual and conversational.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Here, it is believed that children begin to understand that writing serves a purpose.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kroll considers the last phase to be the systematic integration phase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] A differentiation and integration between the child's speaking and writing can be seen in this phase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This means that speaking and writing have 'well-articulated forms and functions'; however, they are also integrated in the sense that they use the same system.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] As a result of the individual being aware of the audience, context and reason they are communicating, both written and spoken language are able to overlap and take several forms at this stage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kroll used the four phases to give an explanation and generalise about the development of these two aspects of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The highest significance is placed on the second and third phase, consolidation and differentiation respectively.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It could be concluded that children's written and spoken language, in certain respects, become more similar to age, maturation, and experience; however, they are also increasingly different in other respects.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The content of the skills are more similar, but the approach used for both writing and speaking are different.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When writing and speaking development is looked at more closely it can be seen that certain elements of written and spoken language are differentiating and other elements are integrating, all in the same phase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Perera conducted a survey and her view mirrors that of Kroll to the extent that she used Kroll's four phases.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When a child undergoes initial learning of the written language, they have not yet fully mastered the oral language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It is clear that their written language development is aided by their spoken language; it can also be said that their spoken language development is aided by the development of their written language skills.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Kantor and Rubin believe that not all individuals successfully move into the final stage of integration.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Perera is also aware that it is hard to assign chronological ages to each phase of writing development, because each child is an individual, and also the phases are 'artificial'.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Other than Kroll's theory, there are four principles on early patterns in writing development discussed by Marie Clay in her book *What Did I Write?*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The four principles are recurring principle, the generative principle, the sign principle, and the inventory principle.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The recurring principle involves patterns and shapes in English writing that develop throughout writing development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The generative principle incorporates the idea that a writer can create new meanings by organizing units of writing and letters of the alphabet.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The sign principle is understanding that the word print also involves paper arrangement and word boundaries.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] And lastly, the inventory principle is the fact that children have the urge to list and name items that they are familiar with, and because of this they can practice their own writing skills.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] More recent research has also explored writing development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Myhill concentrated on the development of written language skills in adolescents aged 13 to 15.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Myhill discovered that the more mature writer was aware of the shaping of text, and used non-finite clauses, which mirrored Perera's results (1984).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Other researchers focused on writing development up until late adolescence, as there has been a limited research in this area.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Chrisite and Derewianke recognize that the survey conducted by Perera (1984) is still one of the most significant research studies in the writing development field and believe Perera's study is similar to theirs.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Chrisite and Derewianke (2010) again propose four phases of writing development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The researchers believe that the process of writing development does not stop when an individual leaves formal education, and again, the researchers highlight that these phases are flexible in their onset.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The first phase focuses on spoken language as the main aid for writing development, and the development then takes its course reaching the fourth phase, which continues beyond formal education.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The environment a child develops in has influences on language development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The environment provides language input for the child to process.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Speech by adults to children help provide the child with correct language usage repetitively.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Environmental influences on language development are explored in the tradition of social interactionist theory by such researchers as Jerome Bruner, Alison Gopnik, Andrew Meltzoff, Anat Ninio, Roy Pea, Catherine Snow, Ernest Moerk and Michael Tomasello.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Jerome Bruner who laid the foundations of this approach in the 1970s, emphasized that adult "scaffolding" of the child's attempts to master linguistic communication is an important factor in the developmental process.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] One component of the young child's linguistic environment is child-directed speech (also known as baby talk or motherese), which is language spoken in a higher pitch than normal with simple words and sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Although the importance of its role in developing language has been debated, many linguists think that it may aid in capturing the infant's attention and maintaining communication.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When children begin to communicate with adults, this motherese speech allows the child the ability to discern the patterns in language and to experiment with language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Throughout existing research, it is concluded that children exposed to extensive vocabulary and complex grammatical structures more quickly develop language and also have a more accurate syntax than children raised in environments without complex grammar exposed to them.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This is especially true for children with autism, who may have more difficulty acquiring language, that "rich and responsive" language from an adult gives much more support to the development of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] With motherese, the mother talks to the child and responds back to the child, whether it be a babble the child made or a short sentence.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] While doing this, the adult prompts the child to continue communicating, which may help a child develop language sooner than children raised in environments where communication is not fostered.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Child-directed speech concentrates on small core vocabulary, here and now topics, exaggerated facial expressions and gestures, frequent questioning, para-linguistic changes, and verbal rituals.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] An infant is least likely to produce vocalizations when changed, fed, or rocked.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The infant is more likely to produce vocalizations in response to a nonverbal behavior such as touching or smiling.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Child-directed speech also catches the child's attention, and in situations where words for new objects are being expressed to the child, this form of speech may help the child recognize the speech cues and the new information provided.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Data shows that children raised in highly verbal families had higher language scores than those children raised in low verbal families.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Continuously hearing complicated sentences throughout language development increases the child's ability to understand these sentences and then to use complicated sentences as they develop.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Studies have shown that students enrolled in high language classrooms have two times the growth in complex sentences usage than students in classrooms where teachers do not frequently use complex sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Some language development experts have characterized child directed speech in stages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Primarily, the parents use repetition and also variation to maintain the infant's attention.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Secondly, the parent simplifies speech to help in language learning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Third, any speech modifications maintain the responsiveness of the child.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] These modifications develop into a conversation that provides context for the development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] As these children begin to grow and acquire more language, it is the parenting style of the caretakers of the child that directly influences their language skills and reading comprehension.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] These parenting styles that affect these children are the authoritative and authoritarian.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The styles that are more authoritative have a direct association with an increase in language development and reading comprehension, while the authoritarian style has a negative relationship to family cohesion which negatively impacts language development and reading comprehension.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It is the style of parenting that is used that can determine how well our children can acquire language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] While most children throughout the world develop language at similar rates and without difficulty, cultural and socioeconomic differences have been shown to influence development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] An example of cultural differences in language development can be seen when comparing the interactions of mothers in the United States with their infants with mothers in Japan.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Mothers in the United States use more questions, are more information-oriented, and use more grammatically correct utterances with their 3-month-olds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Mothers in Japan, on the other hand, use more physical contact with their infants, and more emotion-oriented, nonsense, and environmental sounds, as well as baby talk, with their infants.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Specifically in North American culture, maternal race, education, and socioeconomic class influence parent-child interactions in the early linguistic environment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] When speaking to their infants, mothers from middle class "incorporate language goals more frequently in their play with their infants," and in turn, their infants produce twice as many vocalizations as lower class infants.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Mothers from higher social classes who are better educated also tend to be more verbal, and have more time to spend engaging with their infants in language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Additionally, lower class infants may receive more language input from their siblings and peers than from their mothers.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] It is crucial that children are allowed to socially interact with other people who can vocalize and respond to questions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] For language acquisition to develop successfully, children must be in an environment that allows them to communicate socially in that language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Children who have learnt sound, meaning and grammatical system of language that can produce clear sentence may still not have the ability to use language effectively in various social circumstance.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Social interaction is the footing stone of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] There are a few different theories as to why and how children develop language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] One popular, yet heavily debated explanation is that language is acquired through imitation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] This theory has been challenged by Lester Butler, who argues that children do not use the grammar that an adult would use.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Furthermore, "children's language is highly resistant to alteration by adult intervention", meaning that children do not use the corrections given to them by an adult.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] And if a child's parents aren't fluent, the child will still learn to speak fluent sign language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Trask's theory therefore is that children learn language by acquiring and experimenting with grammatical patterns, the statistical language acquisition theory.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] The two most accepted theories in language development are psychological and functional.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Psychological explanations focus on the mental processes involved in childhood language learning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p01] Functional explanations look at the social processes involved in learning the first language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Each component has its own appropriate developmental periods.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babies can recognize their mother's voice from as early as few weeks old.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] It seems like they have a unique system that is designed to recognize speech sound.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Furthermore, they can differentiate between certain speech sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] A significant first milestone in phonetic development is the babbling stage (around the age of six months).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This is the baby's way of practicing his control over that apparatus.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babbling is independent from the language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Deaf children for instance, babble the same way as hearing ones.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] As the baby grows older, the babbling increases in frequency and starts to sound more like words (around the age of twelve months).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] As the children's ability to produce sound develops, their ability to perceive the phonetic contrast of their language develops.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The better they get in mastering the sound, the more sensitive they become to the changes in those sounds in their language once they get exposed to it.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] They learn to isolate individual phonemes while speaking which also serves as the basis of reading.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] From shortly after birth to around one year, the baby starts to make speech sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] At around two months, the baby engages in cooing, which mostly consists of vowel sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] At around four to six months, cooing turns into babbling, which is the repetitive consonant-vowel combinations.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babies understand more than they are able to say.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In this **0–8 months** range, the child is engaged in vocal play of vegetative sounds, laughing, and cooing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Once the child hits the **8–12-month**, range the child engages in canonical babbling, i.e. dada as well as variegated babbling.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This jargon babbling with intonational contours the language being learned.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] From **12–24 months**, babies can recognize the correct pronunciation of familiar words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babies also use phonological strategies to simplify word pronunciation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Some strategies include repeating the first consonant-vowel in a multisyllable word ('TV' → 'didi') or deleting unstressed syllables in a multisyllable word ('banana' → 'nana').
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Within this first year, two-word utterances and two syllable words emerge.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This period is often called the **holophrastic** stage of development, because one word conveys as much meaning as an entire phrase.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For instance, the simple word "milk" can imply that the child is requesting milk, noting spilled milk, sees a cat drinking milk, etc.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] One study found that children at this age were capable of comprehending 2-word sentences, producing 2–3-word sentences, and naming basic colors.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By **24–30 months** awareness of rhyme emerges as well as rising intonation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] One study concludes that children between the ages of 24 and 30 months typically can produce 3–4-word sentence, create a story when prompted by pictures, and at least 50% of their speech is intelligible.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By **36–60 months**, phonological awareness continues to improve as well as pronunciation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] At this age, children have a considerable experience with language and are able to form simple sentences that are 3 words in length.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] They use basic prepositions, pronouns, and plurals.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] They become immensely creative in their language use and learn to categorize items such as recognizing that a shoe is not a fruit.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] At this age, children also learn to ask questions and negate sentences to develop these questions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Over time, their syntax gets more and more unique and complex.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] A study reveals that at this age, a child's speech should be at least 75% intelligible.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By **6–10 years**, children can master syllable stress patterns, which helps distinguish slight differences between similar words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The average child masters about fifty words by the age of eighteen months.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] These might include words such as, milk, water, juice and apple (noun-like words).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Afterwards they acquire 12 to 16 words a day.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By the age of six, they master about 13 to 14 thousand words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The most frequent words include adjective-like expressions for displeasure and rejection such as 'no'.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] They also include social interaction words, such as "please" and "bye".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Type assumption: A new word refers to a type of thing, not just to a particular thing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, when the child hears the word 'sheep' he infers that it is used for the animal type and not only for that particular sheep that he saw.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Basic level assumption: A new word refers to objects that are alike in basic ways (appearance, behavior, etc.).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In other words, when the child hears the word "sheep" he overgeneralizes it to other animals that look like sheep by the external appearance, such as white, wooly and four-legged animal.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Contextual clues are a major factor in the child's vocabulary development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The child uses contextual clues to draw inferences about the category and meaning of new words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By doing so, the child distinguishes between names and ordinary nouns.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, when an object is presented to the child with the determiner "a" (a cat, a dog, a bottle) he perceives it as an ordinary noun.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, when the child hears a noun without the determiner, he perceives it as a name, for instance "this is Mary".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Children usually make correct meaning associations with the words that the adults say.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, sometimes they make semantic errors.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Overextension: When a child says or hears a word, they might associate what they see or hear as more generalized concept than the real meaning of the word.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, if they say "cat", they might overextend it to other animals with same features.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Underextension: It involves the use of lexical items in an overly restrictive fashion.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In other words, the child focuses on core members of a certain category.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example: 'cat' may only refer to the family cat and no other cat, or 'dog' may refer to certain kinds of dogs that the child is exposed to.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Verb meaning: when a pre-school child hears the verb 'fill', he understands it as the action 'pour' rather than the result, which is 'make full'.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Dimensional terms: the first dimensional adjectives acquired are big and small because they belong to the size category.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The size category is the most general one.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Later children acquire the single dimension adjectives, such as, tall-short, long-short, high-low.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Eventually they acquire the adjectives that describe the secondary dimension, such as thick-thin, wide-narrow and deep-shallow.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] From birth to one year, comprehension (the language we understand) develops before production (the language we use).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] There is about a 5-month lag in between the two.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babies have an innate preference to listen to their mother's voice.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Babies can recognize familiar words and use preverbal gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Within the first **12–18 months** semantic roles are expressed in one word speech including agent, object, location, possession, nonexistence and denial.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Words are understood outside of routine games but the child still needs contextual support for lexical comprehension.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] By **3–5 years**, children usually have difficulty using words correctly.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Children experience many problems such as underextensions, taking a general word and applying it specifically (for example, 'cartoons' specifically for 'Mickey Mouse') and overextensions, taking a specific word and applying it too generally (example, 'ant' for any insect).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, children coin words to fill in for words not yet learned (for example, someone is a cooker rather than a chef because a child may not know what a chef is).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] From **6–10 years**, children can understand meanings of words based on their definitions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] They also are able to appreciate the multiple meanings of words and use words precisely through metaphors and puns.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Within these years, children are now able to acquire new information from written texts and can explain relationships between multiple meaning words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The development of syntactic structures follows a particular pattern and reveals much on the nature of language acquisition, which has several stages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] According to O'Grady and Cho (2011), the first stage, occurring between the ages of 12 and 18 months, is called "one-word stage." In this stage, children cannot form syntactic sentences and therefore use one-word utterances called "holophrases" that express an entire sentence.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In addition, children's comprehension is more advanced than their production abilities.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, a child who wants candy may say "candy" instead of expressing a full sentence.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The following stage is the "two-word stage" in which children begin to produce "mini-sentences" that are composed of two words, such as "doggy bark" and "Ken water" (O'Grady & Cho, 2011, p.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] At this stage, it is unclear whether children have an understanding of underlying rules of the language such as syntactic categories, since their "mini-sentences" often lack distinction between the categories.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, children do exhibit sensitivity to sentence structures and they frequently use appropriate word order.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] After several months of speech that is restricted to short utterances, children enter the "telegraphic stage" and begin to produce longer and more complex grammatical structures (O'Grady & Cho, 2011, p.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This stage is characterized by production of complex structures as children begin to form phrases consisting of a subject and a complement in addition to use of modifiers and composition of full sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Children use mostly content words and their sentences lack function words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Throughout the process of syntactic development, children acquire and develop question structures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] According to O'Grady and Cho (2011), at the early stages of language acquisition, children ask yes–no questions by rising intonation alone as they develop awareness to auxiliary verbs only at a later stage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] When auxiliary verbs make their appearance, it takes children a few months before they are able to use inversion in yes–no questions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The development of WH- questions occurs between the ages of two and four, when children acquire auxiliary verbs that then leads to the ability to use inversion in questions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, some children find inversion easier in yes–no questions than in WH- questions, since the position of both the WH- word and the auxiliary verb must change (e.g., "You are going where?" instead of "Where are you going?").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Morphological structures development occurs over a period of several years.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Before language is acquired, children lack any use of morphological structures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The morphological structures that children acquire during their childhood, and even up to the early school years, are: determiners (a, the), -ing inflection, plural –s, auxiliary be, possessive –s, third person singular –s, past tense –ed).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] When children start using these structures, they tend to overgeneralize the rules and project them upon all the words in the language, including irregulars.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, if a child knows the –ed (past tense) there is a possibility that they will say "I eated" (man-mans cat-cats).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] These errors result from overgeneralization of rules.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This overgeneralization is very noticeable: in fact, children do that in less than 25 percent of the time at any point before reducing that percentage.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Then they improve their mastery, which can be tested in various ways, such as the "wug test" (Berko, 1958).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Children often figure out quickly frequent irregular verbs, such as go and buy rather than less common ones, such as win.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This suggests that children must hear the word several hundred times before they are able to use it correctly.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This development of bound morphemes is similar in order among children, for example: -*ing* is acquired before the article *the*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, parents tend to use a different order while speaking to their kids, for example, parents use the article 'the' more frequently than -ing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Children seem to remember morphemes such as –ing better because they contain their own syllables rather than single consonant morpheme, such as plural –s.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Affixes with more than one meaning are more difficult to acquire, e.g., –s functions both as plural noun and singular third.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] As it comes to word formation processes such as derivation and compounding, the earliest derivational suffixes to show up in children's speech are those they hear adults use most frequently.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] (-er as the *'doer' of the action such as walker.) When it comes to compounds, children first make up names for agents and instruments that they don't know by a pattern (N-N), though some of them do not follow the pattern (*cutter grass for grass cutter).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Then, they might have the right structure but the words are inappropriate since English already has words with the intended meaning such as car-smoke = exhaust.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This process points to a preference for building words from other words, thus place less demand on memory than learning an entirely new word for each concept.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Grammar describes the way sentences of a language are constructed, which includes both syntax and morphology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Syntactic development involves the ways that various morphemes are ordered or combined in sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Morphemes, which are basic units of meaning in language, get added as children learn to produce simple sentences and become more precise speakers.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Morphemes can be whole words (like "happy") or parts of words that change meaning of words ("un"happy).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Brown proposed a stage model that describes the various types of morphological structures that are developed in English and the age range within which they are normally acquired.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] From birth to one year, babies can engage in joint attention (sharing the attention of something with someone else).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Infants also can engage in turn taking activities on the basis of their sensitivity to social contingency, which can elicit social responses in the babies from very early on.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] For example, most acquire early sensitivity to the prosodic patterns of social rituals such as peek-a-boo.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] There is a large debate regarding whether or not bilingualism is truly beneficial to children.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Parents of children often view learning a second language throughout elementary and high school education beneficial to the child.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Another perspective dictates that the second language just confuses the child and prevents them from mastering their primary language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Studies have shown that American bilingual children have greater cognitive flexibility, better perceptual skills and tend to be more divergent thinkers than monolingual children between the ages of five and ten.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Better executive functioning skills are likely because bilingual children have to choose one language to speak while actively suppressing the other.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] This builds stronger selective attention and cognitive flexibility because these skills are being exercised more.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In addition, bilingual children have a better understanding of universal language concepts, such as grammar, because these concepts are applied in multiple languages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] However, studies comparing Swedish-Finnish bilingual children and Swedish monolingual children between the ages of five and seven have also shown that the bilingual children have a smaller vocabulary than monolingual children.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In another study throughout America, elementary school English-monolingual children performed better in mathematics and reading activities than their non-English-dominant bilingual and non-English monolingual peers from kindergarten to grade five.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Learning two languages simultaneously can be beneficial or a hindrance to a child's language and intellectual development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Further research is necessary to continue to shed light on this debate.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] In addition to the study of bilingualism in children, similar research is being conducted in adults.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Research findings show that although bilingual benefits are muted in middle adulthood, they are more profound in older age when those who develop dementia experience onset about 4.5 years later in bilingual subjects.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] The increased attentional control, inhibition, and conflict resolution developed from bilingualism may be accountable for the later onset of dementia.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] There is some research that demonstrates that bilingualism may often be misdiagnosed as a language impairment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] A subtopic of bilingualism in the literature is nonstandard varieties of English.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] While bilingualism and nonstandard varieties of English cannot be considered a true language impairment, they are misrepresented in the population of those receiving language interventions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] A language disorder is the impaired comprehension and or use of a spoken, written, or other symbol system.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-development-p02] Olswang and colleagues have identified a series of behaviors in children in the 18–36-month range that are predictors for the need of language intervention.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Estimates of the number of human languages in the world vary between 5,000 and 7,000.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Precise estimates depend on an arbitrary distinction (dichotomy) established between languages and dialects.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Natural languages are spoken, signed, or both; however, any language can be encoded into secondary media using auditory, visual, or tactile stimuli – for example, writing, whistling, signing, or braille.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In other words, human language is modality-independent, but written or signed language is the way to inscribe or encode the natural human speech or gestures.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] All languages rely on the process of semiosis to relate signs to particular meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Oral, manual and tactile languages contain a phonological system that governs how symbols are used to form sequences known as words or morphemes, and a syntactic system that governs how words and morphemes are combined to form phrases and utterances.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The scientific study of language is called linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Critical examinations of languages, such as philosophy of language, the relationships between language and thought, how words represent experience, etc., have been debated at least since Gorgias and Plato in ancient Greek civilization.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Thinkers such as Jean-Jacques Rousseau (1712–1778) have argued that language originated from emotions, while others like Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) have argued that languages originated from rational and logical thought.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Twentieth century philosophers such as Ludwig Wittgenstein (1889–1951) argued that philosophy is really the study of language itself.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Major figures in contemporary linguistics include Ferdinand de Saussure and Noam Chomsky.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Language is thought to have gradually diverged from earlier primate communication systems when early hominins acquired the ability to form a theory of mind and shared intentionality.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This development is sometimes thought to have coincided with an increase in brain volume, and many linguists see the structures of language as having evolved to serve specific communicative and social functions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Language is processed in many different locations in the human brain, but especially in Broca's and Wernicke's areas.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Humans acquire language through social interaction in early childhood, and children generally speak fluently by approximately three years old.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Therefore, in addition to its strictly communicative uses, language has social uses such as signifying group identity, social stratification, as well as use for social grooming and entertainment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Languages evolve and diversify over time, and the history of their evolution can be reconstructed by comparing modern languages to determine which traits their ancestral languages must have had in order for the later developmental stages to occur.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] A group of languages that descend from a common ancestor is known as a language family; in contrast, a language that has been demonstrated not to have any living or non-living relationship with another language is called a language isolate.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] There are also many unclassified languages whose relationships have not been established, and spurious languages may have not existed at all.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Academic consensus holds that between 50% and 90% of languages spoken at the beginning of the 21st century will probably have become extinct by the year 2100.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The English word *language* derives ultimately from Proto-Indo-European **dn̥ǵʰwéh₂s* "tongue, speech, language" through Latin *lingua*, "language; tongue", and Old French *language*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The word is sometimes used to refer to codes, ciphers, and other kinds of artificially constructed communication systems such as formally defined computer languages used for computer programming.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Unlike conventional human languages, a formal language in this sense is a system of signs for encoding and decoding information.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This article specifically concerns the properties of natural human language as it is studied in the discipline of linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] As an object of linguistic study, "language" has two primary meanings: an abstract concept, and a specific linguistic system, e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] When speaking of language as a general concept, definitions can be used which stress different aspects of the phenomenon.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These definitions also entail different approaches and understandings of language, and they also inform different and often incompatible schools of linguistic theory.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Debates about the nature and origin of language go back to the ancient world.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Greek philosophers such as Gorgias and Plato debated the relation between words, concepts and reality.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Gorgias argued that language could represent neither the objective experience nor human experience, and that communication and truth were therefore impossible.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Plato maintained that communication is possible because language represents ideas and concepts that exist independently of, and prior to, language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] During the Enlightenment and its debates about human origins, it became fashionable to speculate about the origin of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Thinkers such as Rousseau and Johann Gottfried Herder argued that language had originated in the instinctive expression of emotions, and that it was originally closer to music and poetry than to the logical expression of rational thought.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Rationalist philosophers such as Kant and René Descartes held the opposite view.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This led to the question of whether philosophical problems are really firstly linguistic problems.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These debates about language in relation to meaning and reference, cognition and consciousness remain active today.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] One definition sees language primarily as the mental faculty that allows humans to undertake linguistic behaviour: to learn languages and to produce and understand utterances.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This definition stresses the universality of language to all humans, and it emphasizes the biological basis for the human capacity for language as a unique development of the human brain.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Proponents of the view that the drive to language acquisition is innate in humans argue that this is supported by the fact that all cognitively normal children raised in an environment where language is accessible will acquire language without formal instruction.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Languages may even develop spontaneously in environments where people live or grow up together without a common language; for example, creole languages and spontaneously developed sign languages such as Nicaraguan Sign Language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This view, which can be traced back to the philosophers Kant and Descartes, understands language to be largely innate, for example, in Chomsky's theory of universal grammar, or American philosopher Jerry Fodor's extreme innatist theory.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These kinds of definitions are often applied in studies of language within a cognitive science framework and in neurolinguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Another definition sees language as a formal system of signs governed by grammatical rules of combination to communicate meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This definition stresses that human languages can be described as closed structural systems consisting of rules that relate particular signs to particular meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This structuralist view of language was first introduced by Ferdinand de Saussure, and his structuralism remains foundational for many approaches to language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Some proponents of Saussure's view of language have advocated a formal approach that studies language structure by identifying its basic elements and then by presenting a formal account of the rules according to which the elements combine in order to form words and sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The main proponent of such a theory is Noam Chomsky, the originator of the generative theory of grammar, who has defined language as the construction of sentences that can be generated using transformational grammars.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Chomsky considers these rules to be an innate feature of the human mind and to constitute the rudiments of what language is.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] By way of contrast, such transformational grammars are also commonly used in formal logic, in formal linguistics, and in applied computational linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In the philosophy of language, the view of linguistic meaning as residing in the logical relations between propositions and reality was developed by philosophers such as Alfred Tarski, Bertrand Russell, and other formal logicians.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Yet another definition sees language as a system of communication that enables humans to exchange verbal or symbolic utterances.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This definition stresses the social functions of language and the fact that humans use it to express themselves and to manipulate objects in their environment.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Functional theories of grammar explain grammatical structures by their communicative functions, and understand the grammatical structures of language to be the result of an adaptive process by which grammar was "tailored" to serve the communicative needs of its users.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This view of language is associated with the study of language in pragmatic, cognitive, and interactive frameworks, as well as in sociolinguistics and linguistic anthropology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Functionalist theories tend to study grammar as dynamic phenomena, as structures that are always in the process of changing as they are employed by their speakers.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This view places importance on the study of linguistic typology, or the classification of languages according to structural features, as processes of grammaticalization tend to follow trajectories that are partly dependent on typology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In the philosophy of language, the view of pragmatics as being central to language and meaning is often associated with Wittgenstein's later works and with ordinary language philosophers such as J.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Austin, Paul Grice, John Searle, and W.O.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] A number of features, many of which were described by Charles Hockett and called design features set human language apart from communication used by non-human animals.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Communication systems used by other animals such as bees or apes are closed systems that consist of a finite, usually very limited, number of possible ideas that can be expressed.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In contrast, human language is open-ended and productive, meaning that it allows humans to produce a vast range of utterances from a finite set of elements, and to create new words and sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This is possible because human language is based on a dual code, in which a finite number of elements which are meaningless in themselves (e.g. sounds, letters or gestures) can be combined to form an infinite number of larger units of meaning (words and sentences).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] However, one study has demonstrated that an Australian bird, the chestnut-crowned babbler, is capable of using the same acoustic elements in different arrangements to create two functionally distinct vocalizations.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Additionally, pied babblers have demonstrated the ability to generate two functionally distinct vocalisations composed of the same sound type, which can only be distinguished by the number of repeated elements.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Several species of animals have proved to be able to acquire forms of communication through social learning: for instance a bonobo named Kanzi learned to express itself using a set of symbolic lexigrams.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Similarly, many species of birds and whales learn their songs by imitating other members of their species.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] However, while some animals may acquire large numbers of words and symbols, none have been able to learn as many different signs as are generally known by an average 4 year old human, nor have any acquired anything resembling the complex grammar of human language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Human languages differ from animal communication systems in that they employ grammatical and semantic categories, such as noun and verb, present and past, which may be used to express exceedingly complex meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] It is distinguished by the property of recursivity: for example, a noun phrase can contain another noun phrase (as in "[[the chimpanzee]'s lips]") or a clause can contain another clause (as in "[I see [the dog is running]]").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Human language is the only known natural communication system whose adaptability may be referred to as *modality independent*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This means that it can be used not only for communication through one channel or medium, but through several.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] For example, spoken language uses the auditive modality, whereas sign languages and writing use the visual modality, and braille writing uses the tactile modality.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Human language is unusual in being able to refer to abstract concepts and to imagined or hypothetical events as well as events that took place in the past or may happen in the future.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Humans have speculated about the origins of language throughout history.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] is one such account; other cultures have different stories of how language arose.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Theories about the origin of language differ in regard to their basic assumptions about what language is.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Some theories are based on the idea that language is so complex that one cannot imagine it simply appearing from nothing in its final form, but that it must have evolved from earlier pre-linguistic systems among our pre-human ancestors.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These theories can be called continuity-based theories.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The opposite viewpoint is that language is such a unique human trait that it cannot be compared to anything found among non-humans and that it must therefore have appeared suddenly in the transition from pre-hominids to early man.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These theories can be defined as discontinuity-based.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Similarly, theories based on the generative view of language pioneered by Noam Chomsky see language mostly as an innate faculty that is largely genetically encoded, whereas functionalist theories see it as a system that is largely cultural, learned through social interaction.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Continuity-based theories are held by a majority of scholars, but they vary in how they envision this development.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Other continuity-based models see language as having developed from music, a view already espoused by Rousseau, Herder, Humboldt, and Charles Darwin.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] A prominent proponent of this view is archaeologist Steven Mithen.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Because language emerged in the early prehistory of man, before the existence of any written records, its early development has left no historical traces, and it is believed that no comparable processes can be observed today.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Theories that stress continuity often look at animals to see if, for example, primates display any traits that can be seen as analogous to what pre-human language must have been like.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Early human fossils can be inspected for traces of physical adaptation to language use or pre-linguistic forms of symbolic behaviour.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Among the signs in human fossils that may suggest linguistic abilities are: the size of the brain relative to body mass, the presence of a larynx capable of advanced sound production and the nature of tools and other manufactured artifacts.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] It was mostly undisputed that pre-human australopithecines did not have communication systems significantly different from those found in great apes in general.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] However, a 2017 study on *Ardipithecus ramidus* challenges this belief.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Scholarly opinions vary as to the developments since the appearance of the genus *Homo* some 2.5 million years ago.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Chomsky is one prominent proponent of a discontinuity-based theory of human language origins.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In March 2024, researchers reported that the beginnings of human language began about 1.6 million years ago.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The study of language, linguistics, has been developing into a science since the first grammatical descriptions of particular languages in India more than 2000 years ago, after the development of the Brahmi script.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Modern linguistics is a science that concerns itself with all aspects of language, examining it from all of the theoretical viewpoints described above.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The academic study of language is conducted within many different disciplinary areas and from different theoretical angles, all of which inform modern approaches to linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The formal study of language is often considered to have started in India with Pāṇini, the 5th century BC grammarian who formulated 3,959 rules of Sanskrit morphology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] However, Sumerian scribes already studied the differences between Sumerian and Akkadian grammar around 1900 BC.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Subsequent grammatical traditions developed in all of the ancient cultures that adopted writing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In the 17th century AD, the French Port-Royal Grammarians developed the idea that the grammars of all languages were a reflection of the universal basics of thought, and therefore that grammar was universal.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In the 18th century, the first use of the comparative method by British philologist and expert on ancient India William Jones sparked the rise of comparative linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The scientific study of language was broadened from Indo-European to language in general by Wilhelm von Humboldt.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Early in the 20th century, Ferdinand de Saussure introduced the idea of language as a static system of interconnected units, defined through the oppositions between them.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] By introducing a distinction between diachronic and synchronic analyses of language, he laid the foundation of the modern discipline of linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In the 1960s, Noam Chomsky formulated the generative theory of language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] According to this theory, the most basic form of language is a set of syntactic rules that is universal for all humans and which underlies the grammars of all human languages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This set of rules is called Universal Grammar; for Chomsky, describing it is the primary objective of the discipline of linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Thus, he considered that the grammars of individual languages are only of importance to linguistics insofar as they allow us to deduce the universal underlying rules from which the observable linguistic variability is generated.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In opposition to the formal theories of the generative school, functional theories of language propose that since language is fundamentally a tool, its structures are best analyzed and understood by reference to their functions.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The framework of cognitive linguistics interprets language in terms of the concepts (which are sometimes universal, and sometimes specific to a particular language) which underlie its forms.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Cognitive linguistics is primarily concerned with how the mind creates meaning through language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Speaking is the default modality for language in all cultures with hearing members.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The production of spoken language depends on sophisticated capacities for controlling the lips, tongue and other components of the vocal apparatus, the ability to acoustically decode speech sounds, and the neurological apparatus required for acquiring and producing language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The study of the genetic bases for human language is at an early stage: the only gene that has definitely been implicated in language production is FOXP2, which may cause a kind of congenital language disorder if affected by mutations.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The brain is the coordinating center of all linguistic activity; it controls both the production of linguistic cognition and of meaning and the mechanics of speech production.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Nonetheless, our knowledge of the neurological bases for language is quite limited, though it has advanced considerably with the use of modern imaging techniques.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The discipline of linguistics dedicated to studying the neurological aspects of language is called neurolinguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Early work in neurolinguistics involved the study of language in people with brain lesions, to see how lesions in specific areas affect language and speech.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In this way, neuroscientists in the 19th century discovered that two areas in the brain are crucially implicated in language processing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The first area is Wernicke's area, which is in the posterior section of the superior temporal gyrus in the dominant cerebral hemisphere.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] People with a lesion in this area of the brain develop receptive aphasia, a condition in which there is a major impairment of language comprehension, while speech retains a natural-sounding rhythm and a relatively normal sentence structure.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The second area is Broca's area, in the posterior inferior frontal gyrus of the dominant hemisphere.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] People with a lesion to this area develop expressive aphasia, meaning that they know what they want to say, they just cannot get it out.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] They are typically able to understand what is being said to them, but unable to speak fluently.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Other symptoms that may be present in expressive aphasia include problems with word repetition.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The condition affects both spoken and written language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Those with this aphasia also exhibit ungrammatical speech and show inability to use syntactic information to determine the meaning of sentences.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This shows that the impairment is specific to the ability to use language, not to the physiology used for speech production.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] With technological advances in the late 20th century, neurolinguists have also incorporated non-invasive techniques such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and electrophysiology to study language processing in individuals without impairments.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Spoken language relies on human physical ability to produce sound, which is a longitudinal wave propagated through the air at a frequency capable of vibrating the ear drum.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] This ability depends on the physiology of the human speech organs.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] These organs consist of the lungs, the voice box (larynx), and the upper vocal tract – the throat, the mouth, and the nose.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] By controlling the different parts of the speech apparatus, the airstream can be manipulated to produce different speech sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The sound of speech can be analyzed into a combination of segmental and suprasegmental elements.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The segmental elements are those that follow each other in sequences, which are usually represented by distinct letters in alphabetic scripts, such as the Roman script.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In free flowing speech, there are no clear boundaries between one segment and the next, nor usually are there any audible pauses between them.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Segments therefore are distinguished by their distinct sounds which are a result of their different articulations, and can be either vowels or consonants.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Suprasegmental phenomena encompass such elements as stress, phonation type, voice timbre, and prosody or intonation, all of which may have effects across multiple segments.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Consonants and vowel segments combine to form syllables, which in turn combine to form utterances; these can be distinguished phonetically as the space between two inhalations.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Acoustically, these different segments are characterized by different formant structures, that are visible in a spectrogram of the recorded sound wave.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Formants are the amplitude peaks in the frequency spectrum of a specific sound.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Vowels are those sounds that have no audible friction caused by the narrowing or obstruction of some part of the upper vocal tract.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] They vary in quality according to the degree of lip aperture and the placement of the tongue within the oral cavity.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Vowels are called *close* when the lips are relatively closed, as in the pronunciation of the vowel [i] (English "ee"), or *open* when the lips are relatively open, as in the vowel [a] (English "ah").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] If the tongue is located towards the back of the mouth, the quality changes, creating vowels such as [u] (English "oo").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] The quality also changes depending on whether the lips are rounded as opposed to unrounded, creating distinctions such as that between [i] (unrounded front vowel such as English "ee") and [y] (rounded front vowel such as German "ü").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Consonants are those sounds that have audible friction or closure at some point within the upper vocal tract.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Consonant sounds vary by place of articulation, i.e. the place in the vocal tract where the airflow is obstructed, commonly at the lips, teeth, alveolar ridge, palate, velum, uvula, or glottis.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Consonants can also be either *voiced or unvoiced*, depending on whether the vocal cords are set in vibration by airflow during the production of the sound.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Voicing is what separates English [s] in *bus* (unvoiced sibilant) from [z] in *buzz* (voiced sibilant).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Some speech sounds, both vowels and consonants, involve release of air flow through the nasal cavity, and these are called *nasals* or *nasalized* sounds.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Other sounds are defined by the way the tongue moves within the mouth such as the l-sounds (called *laterals*, because the air flows along both sides of the tongue), and the r-sounds (called *rhotics*).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] By using these speech organs, humans can produce hundreds of distinct sounds: some appear very often in the world's languages, whereas others are much more common in certain language families, language areas, or even specific to a single language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Human languages display considerable plasticity in their deployment of two fundamental modes: oral (speech and mouthing) and manual (sign and gesture).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] For example, it is common for oral language to be accompanied by gesture, and for sign language to be accompanied by mouthing.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In addition, some language communities use both modes to convey lexical or grammatical meaning, each mode complementing the other.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Such bimodal use of language is especially common in genres such as story-telling (with Plains Indian Sign Language and Australian Aboriginal sign languages used alongside oral language, for example), but also occurs in mundane conversation.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] For instance, many Australian languages have a rich set of case suffixes that provide details about the instrument used to perform an action.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Others lack such grammatical precision in the oral mode, but supplement it with gesture to convey that information in the sign mode.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] In Iwaidja, for example, 'he went out for fish using a torch' is spoken as simply "he-hunted fish torch", but the word for 'torch' is accompanied by a gesture indicating that it was held.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Secondary modes of language, by which a fundamental mode is conveyed in a different medium, include writing (including braille), sign (in manually coded language), whistling and drumming.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] Tertiary modes – such as semaphore, Morse code and spelling alphabets – convey the secondary mode of writing in a different medium.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p01] For some extinct languages that are maintained for ritual or liturgical purposes, writing may be the primary mode, with speech secondary.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] When described as a system of symbolic communication, language is traditionally seen as consisting of three parts: signs, meanings, and a code connecting signs with their meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The study of the process of semiosis, how signs and meanings are combined, used, and interpreted is called semiotics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Signs can be composed of sounds, gestures, letters, or symbols, depending on whether the language is spoken, signed, or written, and they can be combined into complex signs, such as words and phrases.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] When used in communication, a sign is encoded and transmitted by a sender through a channel to a receiver who decodes it.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The rules by which signs can be combined to form words and phrases are called syntax or grammar.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The meaning that is connected to individual signs, morphemes, words, phrases, and texts is called semantics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The division of language into separate but connected systems of sign and meaning goes back to the first linguistic studies of de Saussure and is now used in almost all branches of linguistics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Languages express meaning by relating a sign form to a meaning, or its content.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Sign forms must be something that can be perceived, for example, in sounds, images, or gestures, and then related to a specific meaning by social convention.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Thus, languages must have a vocabulary of signs related to specific meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The English sign "dog" denotes, for example, a member of the species *Canis familiaris*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In a language, the array of arbitrary signs connected to specific meanings is called the lexicon, and a single sign connected to a meaning is called a lexeme.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Not all meanings in a language are represented by single words.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Often, semantic concepts are embedded in the morphology or syntax of the language in the form of grammatical categories.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] All languages contain the semantic structure of predication: a structure that predicates a property, state, or action.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Traditionally, semantics has been understood to be the study of how speakers and interpreters assign truth values to statements, so that meaning is understood to be the process by which a predicate can be said to be true or false about an entity, e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Recently, this model of semantics has been complemented with more dynamic models of meaning that incorporate shared knowledge about the context in which a sign is interpreted into the production of meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Such models of meaning are explored in the field of pragmatics.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In flowing speech, there is no clear division between segments, only a smooth transition as the vocal apparatus moves.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Depending on modality, language structure can be based on systems of sounds (speech), gestures (sign languages), or graphic or tactile symbols (writing).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The ways in which languages use sounds or signs to construct meaning are studied in phonology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Sounds as part of a linguistic system are called phonemes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Phonemes are abstract units of sound, defined as the smallest units in a language that can serve to distinguish between the meaning of a pair of minimally different words, a so-called minimal pair.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In English, for example, the words *bat* [bæt] and *pat* [pʰæt] form a minimal pair, in which the distinction between /b/ and /p/ differentiates the two words, which have different meanings.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] However, each language contrasts sounds in different ways.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] For example, in a language that does not distinguish between voiced and unvoiced consonants, the sounds [p] and [b] (if they both occur) could be considered a single phoneme, and consequently, the two pronunciations would have the same meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] All spoken languages have phonemes of at least two different categories, vowels and consonants, that can be combined to form syllables.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] As well as segments such as consonants and vowels, some languages also use sound in other ways to convey meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Many languages, for example, use stress, pitch, duration, and tone to distinguish meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Because these phenomena operate outside of the level of single segments, they are called suprasegmental.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Some languages have only a few phonemes, for example, Rotokas and Pirahã language with 11 and 10 phonemes respectively, whereas languages like Taa may have as many as 141 phonemes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In sign languages, the equivalent to phonemes (formerly called cheremes) are defined by the basic elements of gestures, such as hand shape, orientation, location, and motion, which correspond to manners of articulation in spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Writing systems represent language using visual symbols, which may or may not correspond to the sounds of spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The Latin alphabet (and those on which it is based or that have been derived from it) was originally based on the representation of single sounds, so that words were constructed from letters that generally denote a single consonant or vowel in the structure of the word.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In syllabic scripts, such as the Inuktitut syllabary, each sign represents a whole syllable.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In logographic scripts, each sign represents an entire word, and will generally bear no relation to the sound of that word in spoken language.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Because all languages have a very large number of words, no purely logographic scripts are known to exist.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Written language represents the way spoken sounds and words follow one after another by arranging symbols according to a pattern that follows a certain direction.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The direction used in a writing system is entirely arbitrary and established by convention.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Some writing systems use the horizontal axis (left to right as the Latin script or right to left as the Arabic script), while others such as traditional Chinese writing use the vertical dimension (from top to bottom).
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] A few writing systems use opposite directions for alternating lines, and others, such as the ancient Maya script, can be written in either direction and rely on graphic cues to show the reader the direction of reading.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In order to represent the sounds of the world's languages in writing, linguists have developed the International Phonetic Alphabet, designed to represent all of the discrete sounds that are known to contribute to meaning in human languages.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Grammar is the study of how meaningful elements called *morphemes* within a language can be combined into utterances.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Morphemes can either be *free* or *bound*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] If they are free to be moved around within an utterance, they are usually called *words*, and if they are bound to other words or morphemes, they are called affixes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The way in which meaningful elements can be combined within a language is governed by rules.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The study of the rules for the internal structure of words are called morphology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The rules of the internal structure of phrases and sentences are called *syntax*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Grammar can be described as a system of categories and a set of rules that determine how categories combine to form different aspects of meaning.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Languages differ widely in whether they are encoded through the use of categories or lexical units.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] However, several categories are so common as to be nearly universal.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Languages organize their parts of speech into classes according to their functions and positions relative to other parts.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] All languages, for instance, make a basic distinction between a group of words that prototypically denotes things and concepts and a group of words that prototypically denotes actions and events.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The first group, which includes English words such as "dog" and "song", are usually called nouns.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] The second, which includes "think" and "sing", are called verbs.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Another common category is the adjective: words that describe properties or qualities of nouns, such as "red" or "big".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Word classes can be "open" if new words can continuously be added to the class, or relatively "closed" if there is a fixed number of words in a class.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In English, the class of pronouns is closed, whereas the class of adjectives is open, since an infinite number of adjectives can be constructed from verbs (e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] "saddened") or nouns (e.g. with the -like suffix, as in "noun-like").
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In other languages such as Korean, the situation is the opposite, and new pronouns can be constructed, whereas the number of adjectives is fixed.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Word classes also carry out differing functions in grammar.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Prototypically, verbs are used to construct predicates, while nouns are used as arguments of predicates.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In a sentence such as "Sally runs", the predicate is "runs", because it is the word that predicates a specific state about its argument "Sally".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Some verbs such as "curse" can take two arguments, e.g.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] A predicate that can only take a single argument is called *intransitive*, while a predicate that can take two arguments is called *transitive*.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Many other word classes exist in different languages, such as conjunctions like "and" that serve to join two sentences, articles that introduce a noun, interjections such as "wow!", or ideophones like "splash" that mimic the sound of some event.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Some languages have positionals that describe the spatial position of an event or entity.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Many languages have classifiers that identify countable nouns as belonging to a particular type or having a particular shape.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In linguistics, the study of the internal structure of complex words and the processes by which words are formed is called morphology.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] In most languages, it is possible to construct complex words that are built of several morphemes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] For instance, the English word "unexpected" can be analyzed as being composed of the three morphemes "un-", "expect" and "-ed".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Morphemes can be classified according to whether they are independent morphemes, so-called roots, or whether they can only co-occur attached to other morphemes.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] These bound morphemes or affixes can be classified according to their position in relation to the root: *prefixes* precede the root, suffixes follow the root, and infixes are inserted in the middle of a root.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Affixes serve to modify or elaborate the meaning of the root.
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Some languages change the meaning of words by changing the phonological structure of a word, for example, the English word "run", which in the past tense is "ran".
[src:sotaro-kita/language-p02] Furthermore, morphology distinguishes between the process of inflection, which modifies or elaborates on a word, and the process of derivation, which creates a new word from an existing one.
